.B
clearIndex(C) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
C = float()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the clear value for the color index buffers
.LP
\fIgl:clearIndex\fR\& specifies the index used by \fBgl:clear/1\fR\& to clear the color index buffers\&. \fIC\fR\& is not clamped\&. Rather, \fIC\fR\& is converted to a fixed-point value with unspecified precision to the right of the binary point\&. The integer part of this value is then masked with 2 m-1, where m is the number of bits in a color index stored in the frame buffer\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
clearColor(Red, Green, Blue, Alpha) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Red = clamp()
.br
Green = clamp()
.br
Blue = clamp()
.br
Alpha = clamp()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify clear values for the color buffers
.LP
\fIgl:clearColor\fR\& specifies the red, green, blue, and alpha values used by \fBgl:clear/1\fR\& to clear the color buffers\&. Values specified by \fIgl:clearColor\fR\& are clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
clear(Mask) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mask = integer()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Clear buffers to preset values
.LP
\fIgl:clear\fR\& sets the bitplane area of the window to values previously selected by \fIgl:clearColor\fR\& , \fIgl:clearDepth\fR\&, and \fIgl:clearStencil\fR\&\&. Multiple color buffers can be cleared simultaneously by selecting more than one buffer at a time using \fBgl:drawBuffer/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
The pixel ownership test, the scissor test, dithering, and the buffer writemasks affect the operation of \fIgl:clear\fR\&\&. The scissor box bounds the cleared region\&. Alpha function, blend function, logical operation, stenciling, texture mapping, and depth-buffering are ignored by \fIgl:clear\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fIgl:clear\fR\& takes a single argument that is the bitwise OR of several values indicating which buffer is to be cleared\&.
.LP
The values are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT\fR\&: Indicates the buffers currently enabled for color writing\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT\fR\&: Indicates the depth buffer\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BUFFER_BIT\fR\&: Indicates the stencil buffer\&.
.LP
The value to which each buffer is cleared depends on the setting of the clear value for that buffer\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
indexMask(Mask) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mask = integer()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Control the writing of individual bits in the color index buffers
.LP
\fIgl:indexMask\fR\& controls the writing of individual bits in the color index buffers\&. The least significant n bits of \fIMask\fR\& , where n is the number of bits in a color index buffer, specify a mask\&. Where a 1 (one) appears in the mask, it\&'s possible to write to the corresponding bit in the color index buffer (or buffers)\&. Where a 0 (zero) appears, the corresponding bit is write-protected\&.
.LP
This mask is used only in color index mode, and it affects only the buffers currently selected for writing (see \fBgl:drawBuffer/1\fR\& )\&. Initially, all bits are enabled for writing\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
colorMask(Red, Green, Blue, Alpha) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Red = 0 | 1
.br
Green = 0 | 1
.br
Blue = 0 | 1
.br
Alpha = 0 | 1
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Enable and disable writing of frame buffer color components
.LP
\fIgl:colorMask\fR\& and \fIgl:colorMaski\fR\& specify whether the individual color components in the frame buffer can or cannot be written\&. \fIgl:colorMaski\fR\& sets the mask for a specific draw buffer, whereas \fIgl:colorMask\fR\& sets the mask for all draw buffers\&. If \fIRed\fR\& is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&, for example, no change is made to the red component of any pixel in any of the color buffers, regardless of the drawing operation attempted\&.
.LP
Changes to individual bits of components cannot be controlled\&. Rather, changes are either enabled or disabled for entire color components\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
alphaFunc(Func, Ref) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Func = enum()
.br
Ref = clamp()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the alpha test function
.LP
The alpha test discards fragments depending on the outcome of a comparison between an incoming fragment\&'s alpha value and a constant reference value\&. \fIgl:alphaFunc\fR\& specifies the reference value and the comparison function\&. The comparison is performed only if alpha testing is enabled\&. By default, it is not enabled\&. (See \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& of \fI?GL_ALPHA_TEST\fR\&\&.)
.LP
\fIFunc\fR\& and \fIRef\fR\& specify the conditions under which the pixel is drawn\&. The incoming alpha value is compared to \fIRef\fR\& using the function specified by \fIFunc\fR\& \&. If the value passes the comparison, the incoming fragment is drawn if it also passes subsequent stencil and depth buffer tests\&. If the value fails the comparison, no change is made to the frame buffer at that pixel location\&. The comparison functions are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_NEVER\fR\&: Never passes\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LESS\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is less than the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_EQUAL\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is equal to the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LEQUAL\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is less than or equal to the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_GREATER\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is greater than the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NOTEQUAL\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is not equal to the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_GEQUAL\fR\&: Passes if the incoming alpha value is greater than or equal to the reference value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_ALWAYS\fR\&: Always passes (initial value)\&.
.LP
\fIgl:alphaFunc\fR\& operates on all pixel write operations, including those resulting from the scan conversion of points, lines, polygons, and bitmaps, and from pixel draw and copy operations\&. \fIgl:alphaFunc\fR\& does not affect screen clear operations\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
blendFunc(Sfactor, Dfactor) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Sfactor = enum()
.br
Dfactor = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify pixel arithmetic
.LP
Pixels can be drawn using a function that blends the incoming (source) RGBA values with the RGBA values that are already in the frame buffer (the destination values)\&. Blending is initially disabled\&. Use \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_BLEND\fR\& to enable and disable blending\&.
.LP
\fIgl:blendFunc\fR\& defines the operation of blending for all draw buffers when it is enabled\&. \fIgl:blendFunci\fR\& defines the operation of blending for a single draw buffer specified by \fIBuf\fR\& when enabled for that draw buffer\&. \fISfactor\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the source color components\&. \fIDfactor\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the destination color components\&. Both parameters must be one of the following symbolic constants: \fI?GL_ZERO\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& , \fI?GL_DST_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& , \fI?GL_DST_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\& , \fI?GL_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA_SATURATE\fR\& , \fI?GL_SRC1_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC1_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\&, and \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\& \&. The possible methods are described in the following table\&. Each method defines four scale factors, one each for red, green, blue, and alpha\&. In the table and in subsequent equations, first source, second source and destination color components are referred to as (R s0 G s0 B s0 A s0), (R s1 G s1 B s1 A s1) and (R d G d B d A d), respectively\&. The color specified by \fBgl:blendColor/4\fR\& is referred to as (R c G c B c A c)\&. They are understood to have integer values between 0 and (k R k G k B k A), where
.LP
k c=2(m c)-1
.LP
and (m R m G m B m A) is the number of red, green, blue, and alpha bitplanes\&.
.LP
Source and destination scale factors are referred to as (s R s G s B s A) and (d R d G d B d A)\&. The scale factors described in the table, denoted (f R f G f B f A), represent either source or destination factors\&. All scale factors have range [0 1]\&.\fIParameter\fR\&(f R f G f B f A)
.br
\fI?GL_ZERO\fR\& (0 0 0 0)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE\fR\&(1 1 1 1)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\& (R s0 k/R G s0 k/G B s0 k/B A s0 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(R s0 k/R G s0 k/G B s0 k/B A s0 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_DST_COLOR\fR\& (R d k/R G d k/G B d k/B A d k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(R d k/R G d k/G B d k/B A d k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& (A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_DST_ALPHA\fR\& (A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_ALPHA\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\& (R c G c B c A c)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(R c G c B c A c)
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\&(A c A c A c A c)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\& (1 1 1 1)-(A c A c A c A c)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA_SATURATE\fR\&(i i i 1)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC1_COLOR\fR\& (R s1 k/R G s1 k/G B s1 k/B A s1 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC1_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(R s1 k/R G s1 k/G B s1 k/B A s1 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\& (A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A)
.br

.LP
In the table,
.LP
i=min(A s k A-A d) k/A
.LP
To determine the blended RGBA values of a pixel, the system uses the following equations:
.LP
R d=min(k R R s s R+R d d R) G d=min(k G G s s G+G d d G) B d=min(k B B s s B+B d d B) A d=min(k A A s s A+A d d A)
.LP
Despite the apparent precision of the above equations, blending arithmetic is not exactly specified, because blending operates with imprecise integer color values\&. However, a blend factor that should be equal to 1 is guaranteed not to modify its multiplicand, and a blend factor equal to 0 reduces its multiplicand to 0\&. For example, when \fISfactor\fR\& is \fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& , \fIDfactor\fR\& is \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&, and A s is equal to k A, the equations reduce to simple replacement:
.LP
R d=R s G d=G s B d=B s A d=A s
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
logicOp(Opcode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Opcode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify a logical pixel operation for rendering
.LP
\fIgl:logicOp\fR\& specifies a logical operation that, when enabled, is applied between the incoming RGBA color and the RGBA color at the corresponding location in the frame buffer\&. To enable or disable the logical operation, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& using the symbolic constant \fI?GL_COLOR_LOGIC_OP\fR\&\&. The initial value is disabled\&.\fIOpcode\fR\&\fIResulting Operation\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_CLEAR\fR\& 0 
.br
\fI?GL_SET\fR\& 1 
.br
\fI?GL_COPY\fR\& s 
.br
\fI?GL_COPY_INVERTED\fR\& ~s 
.br
\fI?GL_NOOP\fR\& d 
.br
\fI?GL_INVERT\fR\& ~d 
.br
\fI?GL_AND\fR\& s & d 
.br
\fI?GL_NAND\fR\& ~(s & d) 
.br
\fI?GL_OR\fR\& s | d 
.br
\fI?GL_NOR\fR\& ~(s | d) 
.br
\fI?GL_XOR\fR\& s ^ d 
.br
\fI?GL_EQUIV\fR\& ~(s ^ d) 
.br
\fI?GL_AND_REVERSE\fR\& s & ~d 
.br
\fI?GL_AND_INVERTED\fR\& ~s & d 
.br
\fI?GL_OR_REVERSE\fR\& s | ~d 
.br
\fI?GL_OR_INVERTED\fR\& ~s | d 
.br

.LP
\fIOpcode\fR\& is a symbolic constant chosen from the list above\&. In the explanation of the logical operations, \fIs\fR\& represents the incoming color and \fId\fR\& represents the color in the frame buffer\&. Standard C-language operators are used\&. As these bitwise operators suggest, the logical operation is applied independently to each bit pair of the source and destination colors\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
cullFace(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify whether front- or back-facing facets can be culled
.LP
\fIgl:cullFace\fR\& specifies whether front- or back-facing facets are culled (as specified by \fImode\fR\&) when facet culling is enabled\&. Facet culling is initially disabled\&. To enable and disable facet culling, call the \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& commands with the argument \fI?GL_CULL_FACE\fR\&\&. Facets include triangles, quadrilaterals, polygons, and rectangles\&.
.LP
\fBgl:frontFace/1\fR\& specifies which of the clockwise and counterclockwise facets are front-facing and back-facing\&. See \fBgl:frontFace/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
frontFace(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Define front- and back-facing polygons
.LP
In a scene composed entirely of opaque closed surfaces, back-facing polygons are never visible\&. Eliminating these invisible polygons has the obvious benefit of speeding up the rendering of the image\&. To enable and disable elimination of back-facing polygons, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_CULL_FACE\fR\&\&.
.LP
The projection of a polygon to window coordinates is said to have clockwise winding if an imaginary object following the path from its first vertex, its second vertex, and so on, to its last vertex, and finally back to its first vertex, moves in a clockwise direction about the interior of the polygon\&. The polygon\&'s winding is said to be counterclockwise if the imaginary object following the same path moves in a counterclockwise direction about the interior of the polygon\&. \fIgl:frontFace\fR\& specifies whether polygons with clockwise winding in window coordinates, or counterclockwise winding in window coordinates, are taken to be front-facing\&. Passing \fI?GL_CCW\fR\& to \fIMode\fR\& selects counterclockwise polygons as front-facing; \fI?GL_CW\fR\& selects clockwise polygons as front-facing\&. By default, counterclockwise polygons are taken to be front-facing\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
pointSize(Size) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Size = float()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the diameter of rasterized points
.LP
\fIgl:pointSize\fR\& specifies the rasterized diameter of points\&. If point size mode is disabled (see \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with parameter \fI?GL_PROGRAM_POINT_SIZE\fR\&), this value will be used to rasterize points\&. Otherwise, the value written to the shading language built-in variable gl_PointSize will be used\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
lineWidth(Width) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Width = float()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the width of rasterized lines
.LP
\fIgl:lineWidth\fR\& specifies the rasterized width of both aliased and antialiased lines\&. Using a line width other than 1 has different effects, depending on whether line antialiasing is enabled\&. To enable and disable line antialiasing, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH\fR\&\&. Line antialiasing is initially disabled\&.
.LP
If line antialiasing is disabled, the actual width is determined by rounding the supplied width to the nearest integer\&. (If the rounding results in the value 0, it is as if the line width were 1\&.) If |&Delta; x|>=|&Delta; y|, \fIi\fR\& pixels are filled in each column that is rasterized, where \fIi\fR\& is the rounded value of \fIWidth\fR\& \&. Otherwise, \fIi\fR\& pixels are filled in each row that is rasterized\&.
.LP
If antialiasing is enabled, line rasterization produces a fragment for each pixel square that intersects the region lying within the rectangle having width equal to the current line width, length equal to the actual length of the line, and centered on the mathematical line segment\&. The coverage value for each fragment is the window coordinate area of the intersection of the rectangular region with the corresponding pixel square\&. This value is saved and used in the final rasterization step\&.
.LP
Not all widths can be supported when line antialiasing is enabled\&. If an unsupported width is requested, the nearest supported width is used\&. Only width 1 is guaranteed to be supported; others depend on the implementation\&. Likewise, there is a range for aliased line widths as well\&. To query the range of supported widths and the size difference between supported widths within the range, call \fBgl:getBooleanv/1\fR\& with arguments \fI?GL_ALIASED_LINE_WIDTH_RANGE\fR\& , \fI?GL_SMOOTH_LINE_WIDTH_RANGE\fR\&, and \fI?GL_SMOOTH_LINE_WIDTH_GRANULARITY\fR\&\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
lineStipple(Factor, Pattern) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Factor = integer()
.br
Pattern = integer()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the line stipple pattern
.LP
Line stippling masks out certain fragments produced by rasterization; those fragments will not be drawn\&. The masking is achieved by using three parameters: the 16-bit line stipple pattern \fIPattern\fR\& , the repeat count \fIFactor\fR\& , and an integer stipple counter s\&.
.LP
Counter s is reset to 0 whenever \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& is called and before each line segment of a \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& (\fI?GL_LINES\fR\&)/ \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& sequence is generated\&. It is incremented after each fragment of a unit width aliased line segment is generated or after each i fragments of an i width line segment are generated\&. The i fragments associated with count s are masked out if
.LP
\fIPattern\fR\& bit (s/factor)% 16
.LP
is 0, otherwise these fragments are sent to the frame buffer\&. Bit zero of \fIPattern\fR\& is the least significant bit\&.
.LP
Antialiased lines are treated as a sequence of 1×width rectangles for purposes of stippling\&. Whether rectangle s is rasterized or not depends on the fragment rule described for aliased lines, counting rectangles rather than groups of fragments\&.
.LP
To enable and disable line stippling, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_LINE_STIPPLE\fR\&\&. When enabled, the line stipple pattern is applied as described above\&. When disabled, it is as if the pattern were all 1\&'s\&. Initially, line stippling is disabled\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
polygonMode(Face, Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Face = enum()
.br
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Select a polygon rasterization mode
.LP
\fIgl:polygonMode\fR\& controls the interpretation of polygons for rasterization\&. \fIFace\fR\& describes which polygons \fIMode\fR\& applies to: both front and back-facing polygons (\fI?GL_FRONT_AND_BACK\fR\& )\&. The polygon mode affects only the final rasterization of polygons\&. In particular, a polygon\&'s vertices are lit and the polygon is clipped and possibly culled before these modes are applied\&.
.LP
Three modes are defined and can be specified in \fIMode\fR\& :
.LP
\fI?GL_POINT\fR\&: Polygon vertices that are marked as the start of a boundary edge are drawn as points\&. Point attributes such as \fI?GL_POINT_SIZE\fR\& and \fI?GL_POINT_SMOOTH\fR\& control the rasterization of the points\&. Polygon rasterization attributes other than \fI?GL_POLYGON_MODE\fR\& have no effect\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE\fR\&: Boundary edges of the polygon are drawn as line segments\&. Line attributes such as \fI?GL_LINE_WIDTH\fR\& and \fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH\fR\& control the rasterization of the lines\&. Polygon rasterization attributes other than \fI?GL_POLYGON_MODE\fR\& have no effect\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FILL\fR\&: The interior of the polygon is filled\&. Polygon attributes such as \fI?GL_POLYGON_SMOOTH\fR\& control the rasterization of the polygon\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
polygonOffset(Factor, Units) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Factor = float()
.br
Units = float()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Set the scale and units used to calculate depth values
.LP
When \fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_FILL\fR\&, \fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_LINE\fR\&, or \fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_POINT\fR\& is enabled, each fragment\&'s \fIdepth\fR\& value will be offset after it is interpolated from the \fIdepth\fR\& values of the appropriate vertices\&. The value of the offset is factor×DZ+r×units, where DZ is a measurement of the change in depth relative to the screen area of the polygon, and r is the smallest value that is guaranteed to produce a resolvable offset for a given implementation\&. The offset is added before the depth test is performed and before the value is written into the depth buffer\&.
.LP
\fIgl:polygonOffset\fR\& is useful for rendering hidden-line images, for applying decals to surfaces, and for rendering solids with highlighted edges\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
polygonStipple(Mask) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mask = binary()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Set the polygon stippling pattern
.LP
Polygon stippling, like line stippling (see \fBgl:lineStipple/2\fR\& ), masks out certain fragments produced by rasterization, creating a pattern\&. Stippling is independent of polygon antialiasing\&.
.LP
\fIPattern\fR\& is a pointer to a 32×32 stipple pattern that is stored in memory just like the pixel data supplied to a \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& call with height and \fIwidth\fR\& both equal to 32, a pixel format of \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\&, and data type of \fI?GL_BITMAP\fR\& \&. That is, the stipple pattern is represented as a 32×32 array of 1-bit color indices packed in unsigned bytes\&. \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& parameters like \fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\& and \fI?GL_UNPACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\& affect the assembling of the bits into a stipple pattern\&. Pixel transfer operations (shift, offset, pixel map) are not applied to the stipple image, however\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a stipple pattern is specified, \fIPattern\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
To enable and disable polygon stippling, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_POLYGON_STIPPLE\fR\&\&. Polygon stippling is initially disabled\&. If it\&'s enabled, a rasterized polygon fragment with window coordinates x w and y w is sent to the next stage of the GL if and only if the ( x w% 32)th bit in the ( y w% 32)th row of the stipple pattern is 1 (one)\&. When polygon stippling is disabled, it is as if the stipple pattern consists of all 1\&'s\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
getPolygonStipple() -> binary()
.br
.RS
.LP
Return the polygon stipple pattern
.LP
\fIgl:getPolygonStipple\fR\& returns to \fIPattern\fR\& a 32×32 polygon stipple pattern\&. The pattern is packed into memory as if \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& with both \fIheight\fR\& and \fIwidth\fR\& of 32, \fItype\fR\& of \fI?GL_BITMAP\fR\&, and \fIformat\fR\& of \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\& were called, and the stipple pattern were stored in an internal 32×32 color index buffer\&. Unlike \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& , however, pixel transfer operations (shift, offset, pixel map) are not applied to the returned stipple image\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_PACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a polygon stipple pattern is requested, \fIPattern\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
edgeFlag(Flag) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Flag = 0 | 1
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Flag edges as either boundary or nonboundary
.LP
Each vertex of a polygon, separate triangle, or separate quadrilateral specified between a \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& / \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& pair is marked as the start of either a boundary or nonboundary edge\&. If the current edge flag is true when the vertex is specified, the vertex is marked as the start of a boundary edge\&. Otherwise, the vertex is marked as the start of a nonboundary edge\&. \fIgl:edgeFlag\fR\& sets the edge flag bit to \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\& if \fIFlag\fR\& is \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\& and to \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& otherwise\&.
.LP
The vertices of connected triangles and connected quadrilaterals are always marked as boundary, regardless of the value of the edge flag\&.
.LP
Boundary and nonboundary edge flags on vertices are significant only if \fI?GL_POLYGON_MODE\fR\& is set to \fI?GL_POINT\fR\& or \fI?GL_LINE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:polygonMode/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
edgeFlagv(Flag) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Flag = {Flag::0 | 1}
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Equivalent to \fBedgeFlag(Flag)\fR\&\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
scissor(X, Y, Width, Height) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
X = integer()
.br
Y = integer()
.br
Width = integer()
.br
Height = integer()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Define the scissor box
.LP
\fIgl:scissor\fR\& defines a rectangle, called the scissor box, in window coordinates\&. The first two arguments, \fIX\fR\& and \fIY\fR\& , specify the lower left corner of the box\&. \fIWidth\fR\& and \fIHeight\fR\& specify the width and height of the box\&.
.LP
To enable and disable the scissor test, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_SCISSOR_TEST\fR\&\&. The test is initially disabled\&. While the test is enabled, only pixels that lie within the scissor box can be modified by drawing commands\&. Window coordinates have integer values at the shared corners of frame buffer pixels\&. glScissor(0,0,1,1) allows modification of only the lower left pixel in the window, and glScissor(0,0,0,0) doesn\&'t allow modification of any pixels in the window\&.
.LP
When the scissor test is disabled, it is as though the scissor box includes the entire window\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
clipPlane(Plane, Equation) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Plane = enum()
.br
Equation = {float(), float(), float(), float()}
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify a plane against which all geometry is clipped
.LP
Geometry is always clipped against the boundaries of a six-plane frustum in \fIx\fR\&, \fIy\fR\& , and \fIz\fR\&\&. \fIgl:clipPlane\fR\& allows the specification of additional planes, not necessarily perpendicular to the \fIx\fR\&, \fIy\fR\&, or \fIz\fR\& axis, against which all geometry is clipped\&. To determine the maximum number of additional clipping planes, call \fBgl:getBooleanv/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_MAX_CLIP_PLANES\fR\&\&. All implementations support at least six such clipping planes\&. Because the resulting clipping region is the intersection of the defined half-spaces, it is always convex\&.
.LP
\fIgl:clipPlane\fR\& specifies a half-space using a four-component plane equation\&. When \fIgl:clipPlane\fR\& is called, \fIEquation\fR\& is transformed by the inverse of the modelview matrix and stored in the resulting eye coordinates\&. Subsequent changes to the modelview matrix have no effect on the stored plane-equation components\&. If the dot product of the eye coordinates of a vertex with the stored plane equation components is positive or zero, the vertex is \fIin\fR\& with respect to that clipping plane\&. Otherwise, it is \fIout\fR\&\&.
.LP
To enable and disable clipping planes, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with the argument \fI?GL_CLIP_PLANE\fR\&\fIi\fR\&, where \fIi\fR\& is the plane number\&.
.LP
All clipping planes are initially defined as (0, 0, 0, 0) in eye coordinates and are disabled\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
getClipPlane(Plane) -> {float(), float(), float(), float()}
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Plane = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Return the coefficients of the specified clipping plane
.LP
\fIgl:getClipPlane\fR\& returns in \fIEquation\fR\& the four coefficients of the plane equation for \fIPlane\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
drawBuffer(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify which color buffers are to be drawn into
.LP
When colors are written to the frame buffer, they are written into the color buffers specified by \fIgl:drawBuffer\fR\&\&. The specifications are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_NONE\fR\&: No color buffers are written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRONT_LEFT\fR\&: Only the front left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRONT_RIGHT\fR\&: Only the front right color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BACK_LEFT\fR\&: Only the back left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BACK_RIGHT\fR\&: Only the back right color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRONT\fR\&: Only the front left and front right color buffers are written\&. If there is no front right color buffer, only the front left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BACK\fR\&: Only the back left and back right color buffers are written\&. If there is no back right color buffer, only the back left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LEFT\fR\&: Only the front left and back left color buffers are written\&. If there is no back left color buffer, only the front left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RIGHT\fR\&: Only the front right and back right color buffers are written\&. If there is no back right color buffer, only the front right color buffer is written\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRONT_AND_BACK\fR\&: All the front and back color buffers (front left, front right, back left, back right) are written\&. If there are no back color buffers, only the front left and front right color buffers are written\&. If there are no right color buffers, only the front left and back left color buffers are written\&. If there are no right or back color buffers, only the front left color buffer is written\&.
.LP
If more than one color buffer is selected for drawing, then blending or logical operations are computed and applied independently for each color buffer and can produce different results in each buffer\&.
.LP
Monoscopic contexts include only \fIleft\fR\& buffers, and stereoscopic contexts include both \fIleft\fR\& and \fIright\fR\& buffers\&. Likewise, single-buffered contexts include only \fIfront\fR\& buffers, and double-buffered contexts include both \fIfront\fR\& and \fIback\fR\& buffers\&. The context is selected at GL initialization\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
readBuffer(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Select a color buffer source for pixels
.LP
\fIgl:readBuffer\fR\& specifies a color buffer as the source for subsequent \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage1D/6\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage2D/8\fR\& , and \fBgl:copyTexSubImage3D/9\fR\& commands\&. \fIMode\fR\& accepts one of twelve or more predefined values\&. In a fully configured system, \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\&, \fI?GL_LEFT\fR\&, and \fI?GL_FRONT_LEFT\fR\& all name the front left buffer, \fI?GL_FRONT_RIGHT\fR\& and \fI?GL_RIGHT\fR\& name the front right buffer, and \fI?GL_BACK_LEFT\fR\& and \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& name the back left buffer\&. Further more, the constants \fI?GL_COLOR_ATTACHMENT\fR\&\fIi\fR\& may be used to indicate the \fIi\fR\&th color attachment where \fIi\fR\& ranges from zero to the value of \fI?GL_MAX_COLOR_ATTACHMENTS\fR\& minus one\&.
.LP
Nonstereo double-buffered configurations have only a front left and a back left buffer\&. Single-buffered configurations have a front left and a front right buffer if stereo, and only a front left buffer if nonstereo\&. It is an error to specify a nonexistent buffer to \fIgl:readBuffer\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fIMode\fR\& is initially \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\& in single-buffered configurations and \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& in double-buffered configurations\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
enable(Cap) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Cap = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Enable or disable server-side GL capabilities
.LP
\fIgl:enable\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& enable and disable various capabilities\&. Use \fBgl:isEnabled/1\fR\& or \fBgl:getBooleanv/1\fR\& to determine the current setting of any capability\&. The initial value for each capability with the exception of \fI?GL_DITHER\fR\& and \fI?GL_MULTISAMPLE\fR\& is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. The initial value for \fI?GL_DITHER\fR\& and \fI?GL_MULTISAMPLE\fR\& is \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&\&.
.LP
Both \fIgl:enable\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& take a single argument, \fICap\fR\& , which can assume one of the following values:
.LP
Some of the GL\&'s capabilities are indexed\&. \fIgl:enablei\fR\& and \fIgl:disablei\fR\& enable and disable indexed capabilities\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND\fR\&: If enabled, blend the computed fragment color values with the values in the color buffers\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_CLIP_DISTANCE\fR\&\fIi\fR\&: If enabled, clip geometry against user-defined half space \fIi\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_LOGIC_OP\fR\&: If enabled, apply the currently selected logical operation to the computed fragment color and color buffer values\&. See \fBgl:logicOp/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_CULL_FACE\fR\&: If enabled, cull polygons based on their winding in window coordinates\&. See \fBgl:cullFace/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_CLAMP\fR\&: If enabled, the -w c&le; z c&le; w c plane equation is ignored by view volume clipping (effectively, there is no near or far plane clipping)\&. See \fBgl:depthRange/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_TEST\fR\&: If enabled, do depth comparisons and update the depth buffer\&. Note that even if the depth buffer exists and the depth mask is non-zero, the depth buffer is not updated if the depth test is disabled\&. See \fBgl:depthFunc/1\fR\& and \fBgl:depthRange/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DITHER\fR\&: If enabled, dither color components or indices before they are written to the color buffer\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRAMEBUFFER_SRGB\fR\&: If enabled and the value of \fI?GL_FRAMEBUFFER_ATTACHMENT_COLOR_ENCODING\fR\& for the framebuffer attachment corresponding to the destination buffer is \fI?GL_SRGB\fR\&, the R, G, and B destination color values (after conversion from fixed-point to floating-point) are considered to be encoded for the sRGB color space and hence are linearized prior to their use in blending\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH\fR\&: If enabled, draw lines with correct filtering\&. Otherwise, draw aliased lines\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MULTISAMPLE\fR\&: If enabled, use multiple fragment samples in computing the final color of a pixel\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_FILL\fR\&: If enabled, and if the polygon is rendered in \fI?GL_FILL\fR\& mode, an offset is added to depth values of a polygon\&'s fragments before the depth comparison is performed\&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_LINE\fR\&: If enabled, and if the polygon is rendered in \fI?GL_LINE\fR\& mode, an offset is added to depth values of a polygon\&'s fragments before the depth comparison is performed\&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_POINT\fR\&: If enabled, an offset is added to depth values of a polygon\&'s fragments before the depth comparison is performed, if the polygon is rendered in \fI?GL_POINT\fR\& mode\&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_SMOOTH\fR\&: If enabled, draw polygons with proper filtering\&. Otherwise, draw aliased polygons\&. For correct antialiased polygons, an alpha buffer is needed and the polygons must be sorted front to back\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PRIMITIVE_RESTART\fR\&: Enables primitive restarting\&. If enabled, any one of the draw commands which transfers a set of generic attribute array elements to the GL will restart the primitive when the index of the vertex is equal to the primitive restart index\&. See \fBgl:primitiveRestartIndex/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_ALPHA_TO_COVERAGE\fR\&: If enabled, compute a temporary coverage value where each bit is determined by the alpha value at the corresponding sample location\&. The temporary coverage value is then ANDed with the fragment coverage value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_ALPHA_TO_ONE\fR\&: If enabled, each sample alpha value is replaced by the maximum representable alpha value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_COVERAGE\fR\&: If enabled, the fragment\&'s coverage is ANDed with the temporary coverage value\&. If \fI?GL_SAMPLE_COVERAGE_INVERT\fR\& is set to \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&, invert the coverage value\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_SHADING\fR\&: If enabled, the active fragment shader is run once for each covered sample, or at fraction of this rate as determined by the current value of \fI?GL_MIN_SAMPLE_SHADING_VALUE\fR\& \&. See \fBgl:minSampleShading/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_MASK\fR\&: If enabled, the sample coverage mask generated for a fragment during rasterization will be ANDed with the value of \fI?GL_SAMPLE_MASK_VALUE\fR\& before shading occurs\&. See \fBgl:sampleMaski/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SCISSOR_TEST\fR\&: If enabled, discard fragments that are outside the scissor rectangle\&. See \fBgl:scissor/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_TEST\fR\&: If enabled, do stencil testing and update the stencil buffer\&. See \fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& and \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_SEAMLESS\fR\&: If enabled, cubemap textures are sampled such that when linearly sampling from the border between two adjacent faces, texels from both faces are used to generate the final sample value\&. When disabled, texels from only a single face are used to construct the final sample value\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PROGRAM_POINT_SIZE\fR\&: If enabled and a vertex or geometry shader is active, then the derived point size is taken from the (potentially clipped) shader builtin \fI?gl_PointSize\fR\& and clamped to the implementation-dependent point size range\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
disable(Cap) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Cap = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
See \fBenable/1\fR\&
.RE
.LP
.B
isEnabled(Cap) -> 0 | 1
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Cap = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Test whether a capability is enabled
.LP
\fIgl:isEnabled\fR\& returns \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\& if \fICap\fR\& is an enabled capability and returns \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& otherwise\&. Boolean states that are indexed may be tested with \fIgl:isEnabledi\fR\& \&. For \fIgl:isEnabledi\fR\&, \fIIndex\fR\& specifies the index of the capability to test\&. \fIIndex\fR\& must be between zero and the count of indexed capabilities for \fICap\fR\& \&. Initially all capabilities except \fI?GL_DITHER\fR\& are disabled; \fI?GL_DITHER\fR\& is initially enabled\&.
.LP
The following capabilities are accepted for \fICap\fR\& :\fIConstant\fR\&\fISee\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_BLEND\fR\&\fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& , \fBgl:logicOp/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_CLIP_DISTANCE\fR\&\fIi\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_COLOR_LOGIC_OP\fR\&\fBgl:logicOp/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_CULL_FACE\fR\&\fBgl:cullFace/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_DEPTH_CLAMP\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_DEPTH_TEST\fR\&\fBgl:depthFunc/1\fR\& , \fBgl:depthRange/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_DITHER\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_FRAMEBUFFER_SRGB\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH\fR\&\fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_MULTISAMPLE\fR\&\fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_POLYGON_SMOOTH\fR\&\fBgl:polygonMode/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_FILL\fR\&\fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_LINE\fR\&\fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_POINT\fR\&\fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_PROGRAM_POINT_SIZE\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_PRIMITIVE_RESTART\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\& , \fBgl:primitiveRestartIndex/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_ALPHA_TO_COVERAGE\fR\&\fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_ALPHA_TO_ONE\fR\&\fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_COVERAGE\fR\&\fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_MASK\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_SCISSOR_TEST\fR\&\fBgl:scissor/4\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_STENCIL_TEST\fR\&\fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& , \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBEMAP_SEAMLESS\fR\&\fBgl:enable/1\fR\&
.br

.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
enableClientState(Cap) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Cap = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Enable or disable client-side capability
.LP
\fIgl:enableClientState\fR\& and \fBgl:enableClientState/1\fR\& enable or disable individual client-side capabilities\&. By default, all client-side capabilities are disabled\&. Both \fIgl:enableClientState\fR\& and \fBgl:enableClientState/1\fR\& take a single argument, \fICap\fR\& , which can assume one of the following values:
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the color array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:colorPointer/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_EDGE_FLAG_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the edge flag array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:edgeFlagPointer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_COORD_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the fog coordinate array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:fogCoordPointer/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_INDEX_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the index array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:indexPointer/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NORMAL_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the normal array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:normalPointer/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SECONDARY_COLOR_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the secondary color array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:colorPointer/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_COORD_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the texture coordinate array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:texCoordPointer/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VERTEX_ARRAY\fR\&: If enabled, the vertex array is enabled for writing and used during rendering when \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , or see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& is called\&. See \fBgl:vertexPointer/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
