.LP
Return the value or values of a selected parameter
.LP
These four commands return values for simple state variables in GL\&. \fIPname\fR\& is a symbolic constant indicating the state variable to be returned, and \fIParams\fR\& is a pointer to an array of the indicated type in which to place the returned data\&.
.LP
Type conversion is performed if \fIParams\fR\& has a different type than the state variable value being requested\&. If \fIgl:getBooleanv\fR\& is called, a floating-point (or integer) value is converted to \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& if and only if it is 0\&.0 (or 0)\&. Otherwise, it is converted to \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&\&. If \fIgl:getIntegerv\fR\& is called, boolean values are returned as \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\& or \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&, and most floating-point values are rounded to the nearest integer value\&. Floating-point colors and normals, however, are returned with a linear mapping that maps 1\&.0 to the most positive representable integer value and -1\&.0 to the most negative representable integer value\&. If \fIgl:getFloatv\fR\& or \fIgl:getDoublev\fR\& is called, boolean values are returned as \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\& or \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&, and integer values are converted to floating-point values\&.
.LP
The following symbolic constants are accepted by \fIPname\fR\& :
.LP
\fI?GL_ACTIVE_TEXTURE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value indicating the active multitexture unit\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_TEXTURE0\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:activeTexture/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_ALIASED_LINE_WIDTH_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a pair of values indicating the range of widths supported for aliased lines\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_ARRAY_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the buffer object currently bound to the target \fI?GL_ARRAY_BUFFER\fR\&\&. If no buffer object is bound to this target, 0 is returned\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether blending is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_COLOR\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns four values, the red, green, blue, and alpha values which are the components of the blend color\&. See \fBgl:blendColor/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_DST_ALPHA\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the symbolic constant identifying the alpha destination blend function\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ZERO\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& and \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_DST_RGB\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the symbolic constant identifying the RGB destination blend function\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ZERO\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& and \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_EQUATION_RGB\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating whether the RGB blend equation is \fI?GL_FUNC_ADD\fR\&, \fI?GL_FUNC_SUBTRACT\fR\&, \fI?GL_FUNC_REVERSE_SUBTRACT\fR\& , \fI?GL_MIN\fR\& or \fI?GL_MAX\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendEquationSeparate/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_EQUATION_ALPHA\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating whether the Alpha blend equation is \fI?GL_FUNC_ADD\fR\&, \fI?GL_FUNC_SUBTRACT\fR\& , \fI?GL_FUNC_REVERSE_SUBTRACT\fR\&, \fI?GL_MIN\fR\& or \fI?GL_MAX\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendEquationSeparate/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the symbolic constant identifying the alpha source blend function\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ONE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& and \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLEND_SRC_RGB\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the symbolic constant identifying the RGB source blend function\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ONE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& and \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_CLEAR_VALUE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns four values: the red, green, blue, and alpha values used to clear the color buffers\&. Integer values, if requested, are linearly mapped from the internal floating-point representation such that 1\&.0 returns the most positive representable integer value, and -1\&.0 returns the most negative representable integer value\&. The initial value is (0, 0, 0, 0)\&. See \fBgl:clearColor/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_LOGIC_OP\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether a fragment\&'s RGBA color values are merged into the framebuffer using a logical operation\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:logicOp/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_WRITEMASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns four boolean values: the red, green, blue, and alpha write enables for the color buffers\&. The initial value is (\fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&, \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&, \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&, \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&)\&. See \fBgl:colorMask/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COMPRESSED_TEXTURE_FORMATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a list of symbolic constants of length \fI?GL_NUM_COMPRESSED_TEXTURE_FORMATS\fR\& indicating which compressed texture formats are available\&. See \fBgl:compressedTexImage2D/8\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_CONTEXT_FLAGS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the flags with which the context was created (such as debugging functionality)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_CULL_FACE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether polygon culling is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:cullFace/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_CURRENT_PROGRAM\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the name of the program object that is currently active, or 0 if no program object is active\&. See \fBgl:useProgram/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_CLEAR_VALUE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the value that is used to clear the depth buffer\&. Integer values, if requested, are linearly mapped from the internal floating-point representation such that 1\&.0 returns the most positive representable integer value, and -1\&.0 returns the most negative representable integer value\&. The initial value is 1\&. See \fBgl:clearDepth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_FUNC\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the symbolic constant that indicates the depth comparison function\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_LESS\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:depthFunc/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns two values: the near and far mapping limits for the depth buffer\&. Integer values, if requested, are linearly mapped from the internal floating-point representation such that 1\&.0 returns the most positive representable integer value, and -1\&.0 returns the most negative representable integer value\&. The initial value is (0, 1)\&. See \fBgl:depthRange/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_TEST\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether depth testing of fragments is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:depthFunc/1\fR\& and \fBgl:depthRange/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_WRITEMASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating if the depth buffer is enabled for writing\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:depthMask/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DITHER\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether dithering of fragment colors and indices is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DOUBLEBUFFER\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether double buffering is supported\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DRAW_BUFFER\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating which buffers are being drawn to\&. See \fBgl:drawBuffer/1\fR\& \&. The initial value is \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& if there are back buffers, otherwise it is \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DRAW_BUFFER\fR\&\fIi\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating which buffers are being drawn to by the corresponding output color\&. See \fBgl:drawBuffers/1\fR\& \&. The initial value of \fI?GL_DRAW_BUFFER0\fR\& is \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& if there are back buffers, otherwise it is \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\&\&. The initial values of draw buffers for all other output colors is \fI?GL_NONE\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DRAW_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the name of the framebuffer object currently bound to the \fI?GL_DRAW_FRAMEBUFFER\fR\& target\&. If the default framebuffer is bound, this value will be zero\&. The initial value is zero\&. See \fBgl:bindFramebuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_READ_FRAMEBUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the name of the framebuffer object currently bound to the \fI?GL_READ_FRAMEBUFFER\fR\& target\&. If the default framebuffer is bound, this value will be zero\&. The initial value is zero\&. See \fBgl:bindFramebuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_ELEMENT_ARRAY_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the buffer object currently bound to the target \fI?GL_ELEMENT_ARRAY_BUFFER\fR\&\&. If no buffer object is bound to this target, 0 is returned\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FRAGMENT_SHADER_DERIVATIVE_HINT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating the mode of the derivative accuracy hint for fragment shaders\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_DONT_CARE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:hint/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_IMPLEMENTATION_COLOR_READ_FORMAT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single GLenum value indicating the implementation\&'s preferred pixel data format\&. See \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_IMPLEMENTATION_COLOR_READ_TYPE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single GLenum value indicating the implementation\&'s preferred pixel data type\&. See \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether antialiasing of lines is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_SMOOTH_HINT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating the mode of the line antialiasing hint\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_DONT_CARE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:hint/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_WIDTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the line width as specified with \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&. The initial value is 1\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LAYER_PROVOKING_VERTEX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the implementation dependent specifc vertex of a primitive that is used to select the rendering layer\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_PROVOKING_VERTEX\fR\&, then the vertex selection follows the convention specified by \fBgl:provokingVertex/1\fR\& \&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_FIRST_VERTEX_CONVENTION\fR\&, then the selection is always taken from the first vertex in the primitive\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_LAST_VERTEX_CONVENTION\fR\& , then the selection is always taken from the last vertex in the primitive\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_UNDEFINED_VERTEX\fR\&, then the selection is not guaranteed to be taken from any specific vertex in the primitive\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_WIDTH_GRANULARITY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the width difference between adjacent supported widths for antialiased lines\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_WIDTH_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns two values: the smallest and largest supported widths for antialiased lines\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LOGIC_OP_MODE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating the selected logic operation mode\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_COPY\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:logicOp/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAJOR_VERSION\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the major version number of the OpenGL API supported by the current context\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_3D_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a rough estimate of the largest 3D texture that the GL can handle\&. The value must be at least 64\&. Use \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_3D\fR\& to determine if a texture is too large\&. See \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_ARRAY_TEXTURE_LAYERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value indicates the maximum number of layers allowed in an array texture, and must be at least 256\&. See \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_CLIP_DISTANCES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of application-defined clipping distances\&. The value must be at least 8\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COLOR_TEXTURE_SAMPLES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of samples in a color multisample texture\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to all active shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_FRAGMENT_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of words for fragment shader uniform variables in all uniform blocks (including default)\&. The value must be at least 1\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_GEOMETRY_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of words for geometry shader uniform variables in all uniform blocks (including default)\&. The value must be at least 1\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_TEXTURE_IMAGE_UNITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum supported texture image units that can be used to access texture maps from the vertex shader and the fragment processor combined\&. If both the vertex shader and the fragment processing stage access the same texture image unit, then that counts as using two texture image units against this limit\&. The value must be at least 48\&. See \fBgl:activeTexture/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_UNIFORM_BLOCKS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of uniform blocks per program\&. The value must be at least 36\&. See \fBgl:uniformBlockBinding/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_COMBINED_VERTEX_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of words for vertex shader uniform variables in all uniform blocks (including default)\&. The value must be at least 1\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_CUBE_MAP_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value gives a rough estimate of the largest cube-map texture that the GL can handle\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. Use \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP\fR\& to determine if a texture is too large\&. See \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_DEPTH_TEXTURE_SAMPLES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of samples in a multisample depth or depth-stencil texture\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_DRAW_BUFFERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of simultaneous outputs that may be written in a fragment shader\&. The value must be at least 8\&. See \fBgl:drawBuffers/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_DUALSOURCE_DRAW_BUFFERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of active draw buffers when using dual-source blending\&. The value must be at least 1\&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& and \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_ELEMENTS_INDICES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the recommended maximum number of vertex array indices\&. See \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_ELEMENTS_VERTICES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the recommended maximum number of vertex array vertices\&. See \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to fragment shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_INPUT_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of components of the inputs read by the fragment shader, which must be at least 128\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of individual floating-point, integer, or boolean values that can be held in uniform variable storage for a fragment shader\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_UNIFORM_VECTORS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of individual 4-vectors of floating-point, integer, or boolean values that can be held in uniform variable storage for a fragment shader\&. The value is equal to the value of \fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\& divided by 4 and must be at least 256\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_FRAGMENT_UNIFORM_BLOCKS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of uniform blocks per fragment shader\&. The value must be at least 12\&. See \fBgl:uniformBlockBinding/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to geometry shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_INPUT_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of components of inputs read by a geometry shader, which must be at least 64\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_OUTPUT_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of components of outputs written by a geometry shader, which must be at least 128\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_TEXTURE_IMAGE_UNITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum supported texture image units that can be used to access texture maps from the geometry shader\&. The value must be at least 16\&. See \fBgl:activeTexture/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_UNIFORM_BLOCKS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of uniform blocks per geometry shader\&. The value must be at least 12\&. See \fBgl:uniformBlockBinding/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_GEOMETRY_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of individual floating-point, integer, or boolean values that can be held in uniform variable storage for a geometry shader\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_INTEGER_SAMPLES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of samples supported in integer format multisample buffers\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MIN_MAP_BUFFER_ALIGNMENT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the minimum alignment in basic machine units of pointers returned fromsee \fIglMapBuffer\fR\& and see \fIglMapBufferRange\fR\& \&. This value must be a power of two and must be at least 64\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_PROGRAM_TEXEL_OFFSET\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum texel offset allowed in a texture lookup, which must be at least 7\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MIN_PROGRAM_TEXEL_OFFSET\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the minimum texel offset allowed in a texture lookup, which must be at most -8\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_RECTANGLE_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value gives a rough estimate of the largest rectangular texture that the GL can handle\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. Use \fI?GL_PROXY_RECTANGLE_TEXTURE\fR\& to determine if a texture is too large\&. See \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_RENDERBUFFER_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value indicates the maximum supported size for renderbuffers\&. See \fBgl:framebufferRenderbuffer/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_SAMPLE_MASK_WORDS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of sample mask words\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_SERVER_WAIT_TIMEOUT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum \fBgl:waitSync/3\fR\& timeout interval\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TESS_CONTROL_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to tessellation control shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TESS_EVALUATION_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to tessellation evaluation shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TEXTURE_BUFFER_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value gives the maximum number of texels allowed in the texel array of a texture buffer object\&. Value must be at least 65536\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TEXTURE_IMAGE_UNITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum supported texture image units that can be used to access texture maps from the fragment shader\&. The value must be at least 16\&. See \fBgl:activeTexture/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TEXTURE_LOD_BIAS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum, absolute value of the texture level-of-detail bias\&. The value must be at least 2\&.0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. The value gives a rough estimate of the largest texture that the GL can handle\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. Use a proxy texture target such as \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_1D\fR\& or \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_2D\fR\& to determine if a texture is too large\&. See \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& and \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_UNIFORM_BUFFER_BINDINGS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of uniform buffer binding points on the context, which must be at least 36\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_UNIFORM_BLOCK_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum size in basic machine units of a uniform block, which must be at least 16384\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VARYING_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number components for varying variables, which must be at least 60\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VARYING_VECTORS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number 4-vectors for varying variables, which is equal to the value of \fI?GL_MAX_VARYING_COMPONENTS\fR\& and must be at least 15\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VARYING_FLOATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of interpolators available for processing varying variables used by vertex and fragment shaders\&. This value represents the number of individual floating-point values that can be interpolated; varying variables declared as vectors, matrices, and arrays will all consume multiple interpolators\&. The value must be at least 32\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_ATOMIC_COUNTERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the maximum number of atomic counters available to vertex shaders\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_ATTRIBS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of 4-component generic vertex attributes accessible to a vertex shader\&. The value must be at least 16\&. See \fBgl:vertexAttrib1d/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_TEXTURE_IMAGE_UNITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum supported texture image units that can be used to access texture maps from the vertex shader\&. The value may be at least 16\&. See \fBgl:activeTexture/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of individual floating-point, integer, or boolean values that can be held in uniform variable storage for a vertex shader\&. The value must be at least 1024\&. See \fBgl:uniform1f/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_UNIFORM_VECTORS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of 4-vectors that may be held in uniform variable storage for the vertex shader\&. The value of \fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_UNIFORM_VECTORS\fR\& is equal to the value of \fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_UNIFORM_COMPONENTS\fR\& and must be at least 256\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_OUTPUT_COMPONENTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of components of output written by a vertex shader, which must be at least 64\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VERTEX_UNIFORM_BLOCKS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of uniform blocks per vertex shader\&. The value must be at least 12\&. See \fBgl:uniformBlockBinding/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VIEWPORT_DIMS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns two values: the maximum supported width and height of the viewport\&. These must be at least as large as the visible dimensions of the display being rendered to\&. See \fBgl:viewport/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_VIEWPORTS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the maximum number of simultaneous viewports that are supported\&. The value must be at least 16\&. See \fBgl:viewportIndexedf/5\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MINOR_VERSION\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the minor version number of the OpenGL API supported by the current context\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NUM_COMPRESSED_TEXTURE_FORMATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single integer value indicating the number of available compressed texture formats\&. The minimum value is 4\&. See \fBgl:compressedTexImage2D/8\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NUM_EXTENSIONS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of extensions supported by the GL implementation for the current context\&. See \fBgl:getString/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NUM_PROGRAM_BINARY_FORMATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of program binary formats supported by the implementation\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_NUM_SHADER_BINARY_FORMATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of binary shader formats supported by the implementation\&. If this value is greater than zero, then the implementation supports loading binary shaders\&. If it is zero, then the loading of binary shaders by the implementation is not supported\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the byte alignment used for writing pixel data to memory\&. The initial value is 4\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the image height used for writing pixel data to memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether single-bit pixels being written to memory are written first to the least significant bit of each unsigned byte\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the row length used for writing pixel data to memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_IMAGES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of pixel images skipped before the first pixel is written into memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of pixel locations skipped before the first pixel is written into memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of rows of pixel locations skipped before the first pixel is written into memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether the bytes of two-byte and four-byte pixel indices and components are swapped before being written to memory\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PIXEL_PACK_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the buffer object currently bound to the target \fI?GL_PIXEL_PACK_BUFFER\fR\&\&. If no buffer object is bound to this target, 0 is returned\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the buffer object currently bound to the target \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\&\&. If no buffer object is bound to this target, 0 is returned\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POINT_FADE_THRESHOLD_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the point size threshold for determining the point size\&. See \fBgl:pointParameterf/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PRIMITIVE_RESTART_INDEX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the current primitive restart index\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:primitiveRestartIndex/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PROGRAM_BINARY_FORMATS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& an array of \fI?GL_NUM_PROGRAM_BINARY_FORMATS\fR\& values, indicating the proram binary formats supported by the implementation\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PROGRAM_PIPELINE_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& a single value, the name of the currently bound program pipeline object, or zero if no program pipeline object is bound\&. See \fBgl:bindProgramPipeline/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PROVOKING_VERTEX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the currently selected provoking vertex convention\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_LAST_VERTEX_CONVENTION\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:provokingVertex/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POINT_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the point size as specified by \fBgl:pointSize/1\fR\& \&. The initial value is 1\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POINT_SIZE_GRANULARITY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the size difference between adjacent supported sizes for antialiased points\&. See \fBgl:pointSize/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POINT_SIZE_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns two values: the smallest and largest supported sizes for antialiased points\&. The smallest size must be at most 1, and the largest size must be at least 1\&. See \fBgl:pointSize/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_FACTOR\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the scaling factor used to determine the variable offset that is added to the depth value of each fragment generated when a polygon is rasterized\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_UNITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value\&. This value is multiplied by an implementation-specific value and then added to the depth value of each fragment generated when a polygon is rasterized\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_FILL\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether polygon offset is enabled for polygons in fill mode\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& \&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_LINE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether polygon offset is enabled for polygons in line mode\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& \&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_OFFSET_POINT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether polygon offset is enabled for polygons in point mode\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& \&. See \fBgl:polygonOffset/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_SMOOTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether antialiasing of polygons is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:polygonMode/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON_SMOOTH_HINT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating the mode of the polygon antialiasing hint\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_DONT_CARE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:hint/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_READ_BUFFER\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating which color buffer is selected for reading\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& if there is a back buffer, otherwise it is \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RENDERBUFFER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the renderbuffer object currently bound to the target \fI?GL_RENDERBUFFER\fR\&\&. If no renderbuffer object is bound to this target, 0 is returned\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindRenderbuffer/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_BUFFERS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single integer value indicating the number of sample buffers associated with the framebuffer\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_COVERAGE_VALUE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single positive floating-point value indicating the current sample coverage value\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLE_COVERAGE_INVERT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating if the temporary coverage value should be inverted\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLER_BINDING\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the sampler object currently bound to the active texture unit\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindSampler/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SAMPLES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single integer value indicating the coverage mask size\&. See \fBgl:sampleCoverage/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SCISSOR_BOX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns four values: the x and y window coordinates of the scissor box, followed by its width and height\&. Initially the x and y window coordinates are both 0 and the width and height are set to the size of the window\&. See \fBgl:scissor/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SCISSOR_TEST\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether scissoring is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:scissor/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SHADER_COMPILER\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether an online shader compiler is present in the implementation\&. All desktop OpenGL implementations must support online shader compilations, and therefore the value of \fI?GL_SHADER_COMPILER\fR\& will always be \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SMOOTH_LINE_WIDTH_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a pair of values indicating the range of widths supported for smooth (antialiased) lines\&. See \fBgl:lineWidth/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SMOOTH_LINE_WIDTH_GRANULARITY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value indicating the level of quantization applied to smooth line width parameters\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_FAIL\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken for back-facing polygons when the stencil test fails\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_FUNC\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what function is used for back-facing polygons to compare the stencil reference value with the stencil buffer value\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ALWAYS\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_PASS_DEPTH_FAIL\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken for back-facing polygons when the stencil test passes, but the depth test fails\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_PASS_DEPTH_PASS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken for back-facing polygons when the stencil test passes and the depth test passes\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_REF\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the reference value that is compared with the contents of the stencil buffer for back-facing polygons\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_VALUE_MASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the mask that is used for back-facing polygons to mask both the stencil reference value and the stencil buffer value before they are compared\&. The initial value is all 1\&'s\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_BACK_WRITEMASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the mask that controls writing of the stencil bitplanes for back-facing polygons\&. The initial value is all 1\&'s\&. See \fBgl:stencilMaskSeparate/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_CLEAR_VALUE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the index to which the stencil bitplanes are cleared\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:clearStencil/1\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_FAIL\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken when the stencil test fails\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_FUNC\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what function is used to compare the stencil reference value with the stencil buffer value\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_ALWAYS\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_PASS_DEPTH_FAIL\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken when the stencil test passes, but the depth test fails\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_PASS_DEPTH_PASS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, a symbolic constant indicating what action is taken when the stencil test passes and the depth test passes\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_KEEP\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilOpSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_REF\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the reference value that is compared with the contents of the stencil buffer\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_TEST\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether stencil testing of fragments is enabled\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& and \fBgl:stencilOp/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_VALUE_MASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the mask that is used to mask both the stencil reference value and the stencil buffer value before they are compared\&. The initial value is all 1\&'s\&. See \fBgl:stencilFunc/3\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_WRITEMASK\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the mask that controls writing of the stencil bitplanes\&. The initial value is all 1\&'s\&. See \fBgl:stencilMask/1\fR\& \&. This stencil state only affects non-polygons and front-facing polygons\&. Back-facing polygons use separate stencil state\&. See \fBgl:stencilMaskSeparate/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STEREO\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether stereo buffers (left and right) are supported\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SUBPIXEL_BITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, an estimate of the number of bits of subpixel resolution that are used to position rasterized geometry in window coordinates\&. The value must be at least 4\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_1D\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_1D\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_1D_ARRAY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_1D_ARRAY\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_2D\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_2D\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_2D_ARRAY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_2D_ARRAY\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_2D_MULTISAMPLE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_2D_MULTISAMPLE\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_2D_MULTISAMPLE_ARRAY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_2D_MULTISAMPLE_ARRAY\fR\& \&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BINDING_3D\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the name of the texture currently bound to the target \fI?GL_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:bindTexture/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
