.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the image height used for reading pixel data from memory\&. The initial is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether single-bit pixels being read from memory are read first from the least significant bit of each unsigned byte\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the row length used for reading pixel data from memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_IMAGES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of pixel images skipped before the first pixel is read from memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of pixel locations skipped before the first pixel is read from memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the number of rows of pixel locations skipped before the first pixel is read from memory\&. The initial value is 0\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether the bytes of two-byte and four-byte pixel indices and components are swapped after being read from memory\&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VERTEX_PROGRAM_POINT_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating whether vertex program point size mode is enabled\&. If enabled, and a vertex shader is active, then the point size is taken from the shader built-in gl_PointSize\&. If disabled, and a vertex shader is active, then the point size is taken from the point state as specified by \fBgl:pointSize/1\fR\& \&. The initial value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VIEWPORT\fR\&: When used with non-indexed variants of \fIgl:get\fR\& (such as \fIgl:getIntegerv\fR\& ), \fIParams\fR\& returns four values: the x and y window coordinates of the viewport, followed by its width and height\&. Initially the x and y window coordinates are both set to 0, and the width and height are set to the width and height of the window into which the GL will do its rendering\&. See \fBgl:viewport/4\fR\& \&. When used with indexed variants of \fIgl:get\fR\& (such as \fIgl:getIntegeri_v\fR\&), \fIParams\fR\& returns four values: the x and y window coordinates of the indexed viewport, followed by its width and height\&. Initially the x and y window coordinates are both set to 0, and the width and height are set to the width and height of the window into which the GL will do its rendering\&. See \fBgl:viewportIndexedf/5\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VIEWPORT_BOUNDS_RANGE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns two values, the minimum and maximum viewport bounds range\&. The minimum range should be at least [-32768, 32767]\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VIEWPORT_INDEX_PROVOKING_VERTEX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns one value, the implementation dependent specifc vertex of a primitive that is used to select the viewport index\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_PROVOKING_VERTEX\fR\&, then the vertex selection follows the convention specified by \fBgl:provokingVertex/1\fR\& \&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_FIRST_VERTEX_CONVENTION\fR\&, then the selection is always taken from the first vertex in the primitive\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_LAST_VERTEX_CONVENTION\fR\& , then the selection is always taken from the last vertex in the primitive\&. If the value returned is equivalent to \fI?GL_UNDEFINED_VERTEX\fR\&, then the selection is not guaranteed to be taken from any specific vertex in the primitive\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_VIEWPORT_SUBPIXEL_BITS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the number of bits of sub-pixel precision which the GL uses to interpret the floating point viewport bounds\&. The minimum value is 0\&.
.LP
