.LP
Execute a display list
.LP
\fIgl:callList\fR\& causes the named display list to be executed\&. The commands saved in the display list are executed in order, just as if they were called without using a display list\&. If \fIList\fR\& has not been defined as a display list, \fIgl:callList\fR\& is ignored\&.
.LP
\fIgl:callList\fR\& can appear inside a display list\&. To avoid the possibility of infinite recursion resulting from display lists calling one another, a limit is placed on the nesting level of display lists during display-list execution\&. This limit is at least 64, and it depends on the implementation\&.
.LP
GL state is not saved and restored across a call to \fIgl:callList\fR\&\&. Thus, changes made to GL state during the execution of a display list remain after execution of the display list is completed\&. Use \fBgl:pushAttrib/1\fR\& , \fBgl:pushAttrib/1\fR\& , \fBgl:pushMatrix/0\fR\& , and \fBgl:pushMatrix/0\fR\& to preserve GL state across \fIgl:callList\fR\& calls\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
callLists(Lists) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Lists = [integer()]
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Execute a list of display lists
.LP
\fIgl:callLists\fR\& causes each display list in the list of names passed as \fILists\fR\& to be executed\&. As a result, the commands saved in each display list are executed in order, just as if they were called without using a display list\&. Names of display lists that have not been defined are ignored\&.
.LP
\fIgl:callLists\fR\& provides an efficient means for executing more than one display list\&. \fIType\fR\& allows lists with various name formats to be accepted\&. The formats are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_BYTE\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of signed bytes, each in the range -128 through 127\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned bytes, each in the range 0 through 255\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SHORT\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of signed two-byte integers, each in the range -32768 through 32767\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned two-byte integers, each in the range 0 through 65535\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_INT\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of signed four-byte integers\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned four-byte integers\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of four-byte floating-point values\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_2_BYTES\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned bytes\&. Each pair of bytes specifies a single display-list name\&. The value of the pair is computed as 256 times the unsigned value of the first byte plus the unsigned value of the second byte\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_3_BYTES\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned bytes\&. Each triplet of bytes specifies a single display-list name\&. The value of the triplet is computed as 65536 times the unsigned value of the first byte, plus 256 times the unsigned value of the second byte, plus the unsigned value of the third byte\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_4_BYTES\fR\&: \fILists\fR\& is treated as an array of unsigned bytes\&. Each quadruplet of bytes specifies a single display-list name\&. The value of the quadruplet is computed as 16777216 times the unsigned value of the first byte, plus 65536 times the unsigned value of the second byte, plus 256 times the unsigned value of the third byte, plus the unsigned value of the fourth byte\&.
.LP
The list of display-list names is not null-terminated\&. Rather, \fIN\fR\& specifies how many names are to be taken from \fILists\fR\& \&.
.LP
An additional level of indirection is made available with the \fBgl:listBase/1\fR\& command, which specifies an unsigned offset that is added to each display-list name specified in \fILists\fR\& before that display list is executed\&.
.LP
\fIgl:callLists\fR\& can appear inside a display list\&. To avoid the possibility of infinite recursion resulting from display lists calling one another, a limit is placed on the nesting level of display lists during display-list execution\&. This limit must be at least 64, and it depends on the implementation\&.
.LP
GL state is not saved and restored across a call to \fIgl:callLists\fR\&\&. Thus, changes made to GL state during the execution of the display lists remain after execution is completed\&. Use \fBgl:pushAttrib/1\fR\& , \fBgl:pushAttrib/1\fR\& , \fBgl:pushMatrix/0\fR\& , and \fBgl:pushMatrix/0\fR\& to preserve GL state across \fIgl:callLists\fR\& calls\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
