.B
begin(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Delimit the vertices of a primitive or a group of like primitives
.LP
\fIgl:\&'begin\fR\&\&' and \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& delimit the vertices that define a primitive or a group of like primitives\&. \fIgl:\&'begin\fR\&\&' accepts a single argument that specifies in which of ten ways the vertices are interpreted\&. Taking n as an integer count starting at one, and N as the total number of vertices specified, the interpretations are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_POINTS\fR\&: Treats each vertex as a single point\&. Vertex n defines point n\&. N points are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINES\fR\&: Treats each pair of vertices as an independent line segment\&. Vertices 2 n-1 and 2 n define line n\&. N/2 lines are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_STRIP\fR\&: Draws a connected group of line segments from the first vertex to the last\&. Vertices n and n+1 define line n\&. N-1 lines are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LINE_LOOP\fR\&: Draws a connected group of line segments from the first vertex to the last, then back to the first\&. Vertices n and n+1 define line n\&. The last line, however, is defined by vertices N and 1\&. N lines are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TRIANGLES\fR\&: Treats each triplet of vertices as an independent triangle\&. Vertices 3 n-2, 3 n-1, and 3 n define triangle n\&. N/3 triangles are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TRIANGLE_STRIP\fR\&: Draws a connected group of triangles\&. One triangle is defined for each vertex presented after the first two vertices\&. For odd n, vertices n, n+1, and n+2 define triangle n\&. For even n, vertices n+1, n, and n+2 define triangle n\&. N-2 triangles are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TRIANGLE_FAN\fR\&: Draws a connected group of triangles\&. One triangle is defined for each vertex presented after the first two vertices\&. Vertices 1, n+1, and n+2 define triangle n\&. N-2 triangles are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_QUADS\fR\&: Treats each group of four vertices as an independent quadrilateral\&. Vertices 4 n-3, 4 n-2, 4 n-1, and 4 n define quadrilateral n\&. N/4 quadrilaterals are drawn\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_QUAD_STRIP\fR\&: Draws a connected group of quadrilaterals\&. One quadrilateral is defined for each pair of vertices presented after the first pair\&. Vertices 2 n-1, 2 n, 2 n+2, and 2 n+1 define quadrilateral n\&. N/2-1 quadrilaterals are drawn\&. Note that the order in which vertices are used to construct a quadrilateral from strip data is different from that used with independent data\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_POLYGON\fR\&: Draws a single, convex polygon\&. Vertices 1 through N define this polygon\&.
.LP
Only a subset of GL commands can be used between \fIgl:\&'begin\fR\&\&' and \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& \&. The commands are \fBgl:vertex2d/2\fR\& , \fBgl:color3b/3\fR\& , \fBgl:secondaryColor3b/3\fR\& , \fBgl:indexd/1\fR\& , \fBgl:normal3b/3\fR\& , \fBgl:fogCoordf/1\fR\& , \fBgl:texCoord1d/1\fR\& , \fBgl:multiTexCoord1d/2\fR\& , \fBgl:vertexAttrib1d/2\fR\& , \fBgl:evalCoord1d/1\fR\& , \fBgl:evalPoint1/1\fR\& , \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& , \fBgl:materialf/3\fR\& , and \fBgl:edgeFlag/1\fR\& \&. Also, it is acceptable to use \fBgl:callList/1\fR\& or \fBgl:callLists/1\fR\& to execute display lists that include only the preceding commands\&. If any other GL command is executed between \fIgl:\&'begin\fR\&\&' and \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& , the error flag is set and the command is ignored\&.
.LP
Regardless of the value chosen for \fIMode\fR\& , there is no limit to the number of vertices that can be defined between \fIgl:\&'begin\fR\&\&' and \fBgl:\&'begin\&'/1\fR\& \&. Lines, triangles, quadrilaterals, and polygons that are incompletely specified are not drawn\&. Incomplete specification results when either too few vertices are provided to specify even a single primitive or when an incorrect multiple of vertices is specified\&. The incomplete primitive is ignored; the rest are drawn\&.
.LP
The minimum specification of vertices for each primitive is as follows: 1 for a point, 2 for a line, 3 for a triangle, 4 for a quadrilateral, and 3 for a polygon\&. Modes that require a certain multiple of vertices are \fI?GL_LINES\fR\& (2), \fI?GL_TRIANGLES\fR\& (3), \fI?GL_QUADS\fR\& (4), and \fI?GL_QUAD_STRIP\fR\& (2)\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
