.LP
Specify material parameters for the lighting model
.LP
\fIgl:material\fR\& assigns values to material parameters\&. There are two matched sets of material parameters\&. One, the \fIfront-facing\fR\& set, is used to shade points, lines, bitmaps, and all polygons (when two-sided lighting is disabled), or just front-facing polygons (when two-sided lighting is enabled)\&. The other set, \fIback-facing\fR\&, is used to shade back-facing polygons only when two-sided lighting is enabled\&. Refer to the \fBgl:lightModelf/2\fR\& reference page for details concerning one- and two-sided lighting calculations\&.
.LP
\fIgl:material\fR\& takes three arguments\&. The first, \fIFace\fR\& , specifies whether the \fI?GL_FRONT\fR\& materials, the \fI?GL_BACK\fR\& materials, or both \fI?GL_FRONT_AND_BACK\fR\& materials will be modified\&. The second, \fIPname\fR\& , specifies which of several parameters in one or both sets will be modified\&. The third, \fIParams\fR\& , specifies what value or values will be assigned to the specified parameter\&.
.LP
Material parameters are used in the lighting equation that is optionally applied to each vertex\&. The equation is discussed in the \fBgl:lightModelf/2\fR\& reference page\&. The parameters that can be specified using \fIgl:material\fR\&, and their interpretations by the lighting equation, are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_AMBIENT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains four integer or floating-point values that specify the ambient RGBA reflectance of the material\&. Integer values are mapped linearly such that the most positive representable value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Floating-point values are mapped directly\&. Neither integer nor floating-point values are clamped\&. The initial ambient reflectance for both front- and back-facing materials is (0\&.2, 0\&.2, 0\&.2, 1\&.0)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DIFFUSE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains four integer or floating-point values that specify the diffuse RGBA reflectance of the material\&. Integer values are mapped linearly such that the most positive representable value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Floating-point values are mapped directly\&. Neither integer nor floating-point values are clamped\&. The initial diffuse reflectance for both front- and back-facing materials is (0\&.8, 0\&.8, 0\&.8, 1\&.0)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SPECULAR\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains four integer or floating-point values that specify the specular RGBA reflectance of the material\&. Integer values are mapped linearly such that the most positive representable value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Floating-point values are mapped directly\&. Neither integer nor floating-point values are clamped\&. The initial specular reflectance for both front- and back-facing materials is (0, 0, 0, 1)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_EMISSION\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains four integer or floating-point values that specify the RGBA emitted light intensity of the material\&. Integer values are mapped linearly such that the most positive representable value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Floating-point values are mapped directly\&. Neither integer nor floating-point values are clamped\&. The initial emission intensity for both front- and back-facing materials is (0, 0, 0, 1)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_SHININESS\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies the RGBA specular exponent of the material\&. Integer and floating-point values are mapped directly\&. Only values in the range [0 128] are accepted\&. The initial specular exponent for both front- and back-facing materials is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_AMBIENT_AND_DIFFUSE\fR\&: Equivalent to calling \fIgl:material\fR\& twice with the same parameter values, once with \fI?GL_AMBIENT\fR\& and once with \fI?GL_DIFFUSE\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_INDEXES\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains three integer or floating-point values specifying the color indices for ambient, diffuse, and specular lighting\&. These three values, and \fI?GL_SHININESS\fR\&, are the only material values used by the color index mode lighting equation\&. Refer to the \fBgl:lightModelf/2\fR\& reference page for a discussion of color index lighting\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
