.RS
.LP
Set pixel storage modes
.LP
\fIgl:pixelStore\fR\& sets pixel storage modes that affect the operation of subsequent \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& as well as the unpacking of texture patterns (see \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& ), \fBgl:compressedTexImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:compressedTexImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:compressedTexImage3D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:compressedTexSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:compressedTexSubImage2D/9\fR\& or \fBgl:compressedTexSubImage1D/7\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fIPname\fR\& is a symbolic constant indicating the parameter to be set, and \fIParam\fR\& is the new value\&. Six of the twelve storage parameters affect how pixel data is returned to client memory\&. They are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&: If true, byte ordering for multibyte color components, depth components, or stencil indices is reversed\&. That is, if a four-byte component consists of bytes b 0, b 1, b 2, b 3, it is stored in memory as b 3, b 2, b 1, b 0 if \fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\& is true\&. \fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\& has no effect on the memory order of components within a pixel, only on the order of bytes within components or indices\&. For example, the three components of a \fI?GL_RGB\fR\& format pixel are always stored with red first, green second, and blue third, regardless of the value of \fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\&: If true, bits are ordered within a byte from least significant to most significant; otherwise, the first bit in each byte is the most significant one\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\&: If greater than 0, \fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& defines the number of pixels in a row\&. If the first pixel of a row is placed at location p in memory, then the location of the first pixel of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k={n l(a/s) |(s n l)/a| s>= a s< a)
.LP
components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in a pixel, l is the number of pixels in a row (\fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the width argument to the pixel routine otherwise), a is the value of \fI?GL_PACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\& , and s is the size, in bytes, of a single component (if a< s, then it is as if a= s)\&. In the case of 1-bit values, the location of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k=8 a |(n l)/(8 a)|
.LP
components or indices\&.
.LP
The word \fIcomponent\fR\& in this description refers to the nonindex values red, green, blue, alpha, and depth\&. Storage format \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, for example, has three components per pixel: first red, then green, and finally blue\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\&: If greater than 0, \fI?GL_PACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\& defines the number of pixels in an image three-dimensional texture volume, where \fIimage\fR\& is defined by all pixels sharing the same third dimension index\&. If the first pixel of a row is placed at location p in memory, then the location of the first pixel of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k={n l h(a/s) |(s n l h)/a| s>= a s< a)
.LP
components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in a pixel, l is the number of pixels in a row (\fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the width argument to \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& otherwise), h is the number of rows in a pixel image (\fI?GL_PACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the height argument to the \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& routine otherwise), a is the value of \fI?GL_PACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\& , and s is the size, in bytes, of a single component (if a< s, then it is as if a=s)\&.
.LP
The word \fIcomponent\fR\& in this description refers to the nonindex values red, green, blue, alpha, and depth\&. Storage format \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, for example, has three components per pixel: first red, then green, and finally blue\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\&, \fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\&, and \fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_IMAGES\fR\&
.LP
These values are provided as a convenience to the programmer; they provide no functionality that cannot be duplicated simply by incrementing the pointer passed to \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& \&. Setting \fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\& to i is equivalent to incrementing the pointer by i n components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in each pixel\&. Setting \fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\& to j is equivalent to incrementing the pointer by j m components or indices, where m is the number of components or indices per row, as just computed in the \fI?GL_PACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& section\&. Setting \fI?GL_PACK_SKIP_IMAGES\fR\& to k is equivalent to incrementing the pointer by k p, where p is the number of components or indices per image, as computed in the \fI?GL_PACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\& section\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_PACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\&: Specifies the alignment requirements for the start of each pixel row in memory\&. The allowable values are 1 (byte-alignment), 2 (rows aligned to even-numbered bytes), 4 (word-alignment), and 8 (rows start on double-word boundaries)\&.
.LP
The other six of the twelve storage parameters affect how pixel data is read from client memory\&. These values are significant for \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , and \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\&
.LP
They are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&: If true, byte ordering for multibyte color components, depth components, or stencil indices is reversed\&. That is, if a four-byte component consists of bytes b 0, b 1, b 2, b 3, it is taken from memory as b 3, b 2, b 1, b 0 if \fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\& is true\&. \fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\& has no effect on the memory order of components within a pixel, only on the order of bytes within components or indices\&. For example, the three components of a \fI?GL_RGB\fR\& format pixel are always stored with red first, green second, and blue third, regardless of the value of \fI?GL_UNPACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\&: If true, bits are ordered within a byte from least significant to most significant; otherwise, the first bit in each byte is the most significant one\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\&: If greater than 0, \fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& defines the number of pixels in a row\&. If the first pixel of a row is placed at location p in memory, then the location of the first pixel of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k={n l(a/s) |(s n l)/a| s>= a s< a)
.LP
components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in a pixel, l is the number of pixels in a row (\fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the width argument to the pixel routine otherwise), a is the value of \fI?GL_UNPACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\& , and s is the size, in bytes, of a single component (if a< s, then it is as if a= s)\&. In the case of 1-bit values, the location of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k=8 a |(n l)/(8 a)|
.LP
components or indices\&.
.LP
The word \fIcomponent\fR\& in this description refers to the nonindex values red, green, blue, alpha, and depth\&. Storage format \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, for example, has three components per pixel: first red, then green, and finally blue\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\&: If greater than 0, \fI?GL_UNPACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\& defines the number of pixels in an image of a three-dimensional texture volume\&. Where \fIimage\fR\& is defined by all pixel sharing the same third dimension index\&. If the first pixel of a row is placed at location p in memory, then the location of the first pixel of the next row is obtained by skipping
.LP
k={n l h(a/s) |(s n l h)/a| s>= a s< a)
.LP
components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in a pixel, l is the number of pixels in a row (\fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the width argument to \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& otherwise), h is the number of rows in an image (\fI?GL_UNPACK_IMAGE_HEIGHT\fR\& if it is greater than 0, the height argument to \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& otherwise), a is the value of \fI?GL_UNPACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\&, and s is the size, in bytes, of a single component (if a< s, then it is as if a=s)\&.
.LP
The word \fIcomponent\fR\& in this description refers to the nonindex values red, green, blue, alpha, and depth\&. Storage format \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, for example, has three components per pixel: first red, then green, and finally blue\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\& and \fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\&
.LP
These values are provided as a convenience to the programmer; they provide no functionality that cannot be duplicated by incrementing the pointer passed to \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& or \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& \&. Setting \fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_PIXELS\fR\& to i is equivalent to incrementing the pointer by i n components or indices, where n is the number of components or indices in each pixel\&. Setting \fI?GL_UNPACK_SKIP_ROWS\fR\& to j is equivalent to incrementing the pointer by j k components or indices, where k is the number of components or indices per row, as just computed in the \fI?GL_UNPACK_ROW_LENGTH\fR\& section\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_UNPACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\&: Specifies the alignment requirements for the start of each pixel row in memory\&. The allowable values are 1 (byte-alignment), 2 (rows aligned to even-numbered bytes), 4 (word-alignment), and 8 (rows start on double-word boundaries)\&.
.LP
