.LP
Set pixel transfer modes
.LP
\fIgl:pixelTransfer\fR\& sets pixel transfer modes that affect the operation of subsequent \fBgl:copyPixels/5\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage1D/6\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage3D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& , \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , and \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& commands\&. Additionally, if the ARB_imaging subset is supported, the routines \fBgl:colorTable/6\fR\& , \fBgl:colorSubTable/6\fR\& , \fBgl:convolutionFilter1D/6\fR\& , \fBgl:convolutionFilter2D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:histogram/4\fR\& , \fBgl:minmax/3\fR\& , and \fBgl:separableFilter2D/8\fR\& are also affected\&. The algorithms that are specified by pixel transfer modes operate on pixels after they are read from the frame buffer ( \fBgl:copyPixels/5\fR\& \fBgl:copyTexImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage1D/6\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage2D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexSubImage3D/9\fR\& , and \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& ), or unpacked from client memory ( \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& , and \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& )\&. Pixel transfer operations happen in the same order, and in the same manner, regardless of the command that resulted in the pixel operation\&. Pixel storage modes (see \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& ) control the unpacking of pixels being read from client memory and the packing of pixels being written back into client memory\&.
.LP
Pixel transfer operations handle four fundamental pixel types: \fIcolor\fR\&, \fIcolor index\fR\& , \fIdepth\fR\&, and \fIstencil\fR\&\&. \fIColor\fR\& pixels consist of four floating-point values with unspecified mantissa and exponent sizes, scaled such that 0 represents zero intensity and 1 represents full intensity\&. \fIColor indices\fR\& comprise a single fixed-point value, with unspecified precision to the right of the binary point\&. \fIDepth\fR\& pixels comprise a single floating-point value, with unspecified mantissa and exponent sizes, scaled such that 0\&.0 represents the minimum depth buffer value, and 1\&.0 represents the maximum depth buffer value\&. Finally, \fIstencil\fR\& pixels comprise a single fixed-point value, with unspecified precision to the right of the binary point\&.
.LP
The pixel transfer operations performed on the four basic pixel types are as follows:
.LP
\fIColor\fR\&: Each of the four color components is multiplied by a scale factor, then added to a bias factor\&. That is, the red component is multiplied by \fI?GL_RED_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_RED_BIAS\fR\&; the green component is multiplied by \fI?GL_GREEN_SCALE\fR\& , then added to \fI?GL_GREEN_BIAS\fR\&; the blue component is multiplied by \fI?GL_BLUE_SCALE\fR\& , then added to \fI?GL_BLUE_BIAS\fR\&; and the alpha component is multiplied by \fI?GL_ALPHA_SCALE\fR\& , then added to \fI?GL_ALPHA_BIAS\fR\&\&. After all four color components are scaled and biased, each is clamped to the range [0 1]\&. All color, scale, and bias values are specified with \fIgl:pixelTransfer\fR\&\&.
.LP
If \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is true, each color component is scaled by the size of the corresponding color-to-color map, then replaced by the contents of that map indexed by the scaled component\&. That is, the red component is scaled by \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_R_TO_R_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_R_TO_R\fR\& indexed by itself\&. The green component is scaled by \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_G_TO_G_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_G_TO_G\fR\& indexed by itself\&. The blue component is scaled by \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_B_TO_B_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_B_TO_B\fR\& indexed by itself\&. And the alpha component is scaled by \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_A_TO_A_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_A_TO_A\fR\& indexed by itself\&. All components taken from the maps are then clamped to the range [0 1]\&. \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is specified with \fIgl:pixelTransfer\fR\&\&. The contents of the various maps are specified with \fBgl:pixelMapfv/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
If the ARB_imaging extension is supported, each of the four color components may be scaled and biased after transformation by the color matrix\&. That is, the red component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_RED_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_RED_BIAS\fR\& ; the green component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_GREEN_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_GREEN_BIAS\fR\&; the blue component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_BLUE_SCALE\fR\& , then added to \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_BLUE_BIAS\fR\&; and the alpha component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_ALPHA_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_ALPHA_BIAS\fR\& \&. After all four color components are scaled and biased, each is clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
Similarly, if the ARB_imaging extension is supported, each of the four color components may be scaled and biased after processing by the enabled convolution filter\&. That is, the red component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_RED_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_RED_BIAS\fR\& ; the green component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_GREEN_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_GREEN_BIAS\fR\&; the blue component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_BLUE_SCALE\fR\& , then added to \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_BLUE_BIAS\fR\&; and the alpha component is multiplied by \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_ALPHA_SCALE\fR\&, then added to \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_ALPHA_BIAS\fR\& \&. After all four color components are scaled and biased, each is clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
\fIColor index\fR\&: Each color index is shifted left by \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& bits; any bits beyond the number of fraction bits carried by the fixed-point index are filled with zeros\&. If \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& is negative, the shift is to the right, again zero filled\&. Then \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\& is added to the index\&. \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& and \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\& are specified with \fIgl:pixelTransfer\fR\&\&.
.LP
From this point, operation diverges depending on the required format of the resulting pixels\&. If the resulting pixels are to be written to a color index buffer, or if they are being read back to client memory in \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\& format, the pixels continue to be treated as indices\&. If \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is true, each index is masked by 2 n-1 , where n is \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_I_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_I\fR\& indexed by the masked value\&. \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is specified with \fIgl:pixelTransfer\fR\& \&. The contents of the index map is specified with \fBgl:pixelMapfv/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
If the resulting pixels are to be written to an RGBA color buffer, or if they are read back to client memory in a format other than \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\&, the pixels are converted from indices to colors by referencing the four maps \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_R\fR\&, \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_G\fR\& , \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_B\fR\&, and \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_A\fR\&\&. Before being dereferenced, the index is masked by 2 n-1, where n is \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_R_SIZE\fR\& for the red map, \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_G_SIZE\fR\& for the green map, \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_B_SIZE\fR\& for the blue map, and \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_A_SIZE\fR\& for the alpha map\&. All components taken from the maps are then clamped to the range [0 1]\&. The contents of the four maps is specified with \fBgl:pixelMapfv/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fIDepth\fR\&: Each depth value is multiplied by \fI?GL_DEPTH_SCALE\fR\&, added to \fI?GL_DEPTH_BIAS\fR\& , then clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
\fIStencil\fR\&: Each index is shifted \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& bits just as a color index is, then added to \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\&\&. If \fI?GL_MAP_STENCIL\fR\& is true, each index is masked by 2 n-1, where n is \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_S_TO_S_SIZE\fR\&, then replaced by the contents of \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_S_TO_S\fR\& indexed by the masked value\&.
.LP
