bitmap(Width, Height, Xorig, Yorig, Xmove, Ymove, Bitmap) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Width = integer()
.br
Height = integer()
.br
Xorig = float()
.br
Yorig = float()
.br
Xmove = float()
.br
Ymove = float()
.br
Bitmap = offset() | mem()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Draw a bitmap
.LP
A bitmap is a binary image\&. When drawn, the bitmap is positioned relative to the current raster position, and frame buffer pixels corresponding to 1\&'s in the bitmap are written using the current raster color or index\&. Frame buffer pixels corresponding to 0\&'s in the bitmap are not modified\&.
.LP
\fIgl:bitmap\fR\& takes seven arguments\&. The first pair specifies the width and height of the bitmap image\&. The second pair specifies the location of the bitmap origin relative to the lower left corner of the bitmap image\&. The third pair of arguments specifies \fIx\fR\& and \fIy\fR\& offsets to be added to the current raster position after the bitmap has been drawn\&. The final argument is a pointer to the bitmap image itself\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a bitmap image is specified, \fIBitmap\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
The bitmap image is interpreted like image data for the \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& command, with \fIWidth\fR\& and \fIHeight\fR\& corresponding to the width and height arguments of that command, and with \fItype\fR\& set to \fI?GL_BITMAP\fR\& and \fIformat\fR\& set to \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\& \&. Modes specified using \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& affect the interpretation of bitmap image data; modes specified using \fBgl:pixelTransferf/2\fR\& do not\&.
.LP
If the current raster position is invalid, \fIgl:bitmap\fR\& is ignored\&. Otherwise, the lower left corner of the bitmap image is positioned at the window coordinates
.LP
x w=|x r-x o|
.LP
y w=|y r-y o|
.LP
where (x r y r) is the raster position and (x o y o) is the bitmap origin\&. Fragments are then generated for each pixel corresponding to a 1 (one) in the bitmap image\&. These fragments are generated using the current raster \fIz\fR\& coordinate, color or color index, and current raster texture coordinates\&. They are then treated just as if they had been generated by a point, line, or polygon, including texture mapping, fogging, and all per-fragment operations such as alpha and depth testing\&.
.LP
After the bitmap has been drawn, the \fIx\fR\& and \fIy\fR\& coordinates of the current raster position are offset by \fIXmove\fR\& and \fIYmove\fR\& \&. No change is made to the \fIz\fR\& coordinate of the current raster position, or to the current raster color, texture coordinates, or index\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
readPixels(X, Y, Width, Height, Format, Type, Pixels) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
X = integer()
.br
Y = integer()
.br
Width = integer()
.br
Height = integer()
.br
Format = enum()
.br
Type = enum()
.br
Pixels = mem()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Read a block of pixels from the frame buffer
.LP
\fIgl:readPixels\fR\& returns pixel data from the frame buffer, starting with the pixel whose lower left corner is at location ( \fIX\fR\& , \fIY\fR\& ), into client memory starting at location \fIData\fR\& \&. Several parameters control the processing of the pixel data before it is placed into client memory\&. These parameters are set with \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& \&. This reference page describes the effects on \fIgl:readPixels\fR\& of most, but not all of the parameters specified by these three commands\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_PACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a block of pixels is requested, \fIData\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store rather than a pointer to client memory\&.
.LP
\fIgl:readPixels\fR\& returns values from each pixel with lower left corner at (x+i y+j) for 0<= i< width and 0<= j< height\&. This pixel is said to be the ith pixel in the jth row\&. Pixels are returned in row order from the lowest to the highest row, left to right in each row\&.
.LP
\fIFormat\fR\& specifies the format for the returned pixel values; accepted values are:
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_INDEX\fR\&: Stencil values are read from the stencil buffer\&. Each index is converted to fixed point, shifted left or right depending on the value and sign of \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& , and added to \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\&\&. If \fI?GL_MAP_STENCIL\fR\& is \fI?GL_TRUE\fR\&, indices are replaced by their mappings in the table \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_S_TO_S\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_COMPONENT\fR\&: Depth values are read from the depth buffer\&. Each component is converted to floating point such that the minimum depth value maps to 0 and the maximum value maps to 1\&. Each component is then multiplied by \fI?GL_DEPTH_SCALE\fR\&, added to \fI?GL_DEPTH_BIAS\fR\& , and finally clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_STENCIL\fR\&: Values are taken from both the depth and stencil buffers\&. The \fIType\fR\& parameter must be \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8\fR\& or \fI?GL_FLOAT_32_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8_REV\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RED\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_GREEN\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BLUE\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGR\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGRA\fR\&: Finally, the indices or components are converted to the proper format, as specified by \fIType\fR\& \&. If \fIFormat\fR\& is \fI?GL_STENCIL_INDEX\fR\& and \fIType\fR\& is not \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&, each index is masked with the mask value given in the following table\&. If \fIType\fR\& is \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&, then each integer index is converted to single-precision floating-point format\&.
.LP
If \fIFormat\fR\& is \fI?GL_RED\fR\&, \fI?GL_GREEN\fR\&, \fI?GL_BLUE\fR\&, \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_BGR\fR\& , \fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&, or \fI?GL_BGRA\fR\& and \fIType\fR\& is not \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&, each component is multiplied by the multiplier shown in the following table\&. If type is \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&, then each component is passed as is (or converted to the client\&'s single-precision floating-point format if it is different from the one used by the GL)\&.\fIType\fR\&\fIIndex Mask\fR\&\fIComponent Conversion\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE\fR\& 2 8-1(2 8-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_BYTE\fR\& 2 7-1((2 8-1) c-1)/2
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT\fR\& 2 16-1(2 16-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_SHORT\fR\& 2 15-1((2 16-1) c-1)/2 
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT\fR\& 2 32-1(2 32-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_INT\fR\& 2 31-1((2 32-1) c-1)/2
.br
\fI?GL_HALF_FLOAT\fR\& none c
.br
\fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\& none c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE_3_3_2\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE_2_3_3_REV\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_6_5\fR\& 2 N-1 (2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_6_5_REV\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_4_4_4_4\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_4_4_4_4_REV\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_5_5_1\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_1_5_5_5_REV\fR\& 2 N-1 (2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_8_8_8_8\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_8_8_8_8_REV\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_10_10_10_2\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_2_10_10_10_REV\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8\fR\& 2 N-1(2 N-1) c
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_10F_11F_11F_REV\fR\& -- Special 
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_5_9_9_9_REV\fR\& -- Special 
.br
\fI?GL_FLOAT_32_UNSIGNED_INT_24_8_REV\fR\& none c (Depth Only) 
.br

.LP
Return values are placed in memory as follows\&. If \fIFormat\fR\& is \fI?GL_STENCIL_INDEX\fR\& , \fI?GL_DEPTH_COMPONENT\fR\&, \fI?GL_RED\fR\&, \fI?GL_GREEN\fR\&, or \fI?GL_BLUE\fR\&, a single value is returned and the data for the ith pixel in the jth row is placed in location (j) width+i\&. \fI?GL_RGB\fR\& and \fI?GL_BGR\fR\& return three values, \fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& and \fI?GL_BGRA\fR\& return four values for each pixel, with all values corresponding to a single pixel occupying contiguous space in \fIData\fR\& \&. Storage parameters set by \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& , such as \fI?GL_PACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\& and \fI?GL_PACK_SWAP_BYTES\fR\&, affect the way that data is written into memory\&. See \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& for a description\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
drawPixels(Width, Height, Format, Type, Pixels) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Width = integer()
.br
Height = integer()
.br
Format = enum()
.br
Type = enum()
.br
Pixels = offset() | mem()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Write a block of pixels to the frame buffer
.LP
\fIgl:drawPixels\fR\& reads pixel data from memory and writes it into the frame buffer relative to the current raster position, provided that the raster position is valid\&. Use \fBgl:rasterPos2d/2\fR\& or \fBgl:windowPos2d/2\fR\& to set the current raster position; use \fBgl:getBooleanv/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_CURRENT_RASTER_POSITION_VALID\fR\& to determine if the specified raster position is valid, and \fBgl:getBooleanv/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_CURRENT_RASTER_POSITION\fR\& to query the raster position\&.
.LP
Several parameters define the encoding of pixel data in memory and control the processing of the pixel data before it is placed in the frame buffer\&. These parameters are set with four commands: \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& , \fBgl:pixelTransferf/2\fR\& , \fBgl:pixelMapfv/3\fR\& , and \fBgl:pixelZoom/2\fR\& \&. This reference page describes the effects on \fIgl:drawPixels\fR\& of many, but not all, of the parameters specified by these four commands\&.
.LP
Data is read from \fIData\fR\& as a sequence of signed or unsigned bytes, signed or unsigned shorts, signed or unsigned integers, or single-precision floating-point values, depending on \fIType\fR\& \&. When \fIType\fR\& is one of \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE\fR\&, \fI?GL_BYTE\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT\fR\& , \fI?GL_SHORT\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT\fR\&, \fI?GL_INT\fR\&, or \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\& each of these bytes, shorts, integers, or floating-point values is interpreted as one color or depth component, or one index, depending on \fIFormat\fR\& \&. When \fIType\fR\& is one of \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE_3_3_2\fR\& , \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_6_5\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_4_4_4_4\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_5_5_1\fR\& , \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_8_8_8_8\fR\&, or \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_10_10_10_2\fR\&, each unsigned value is interpreted as containing all the components for a single pixel, with the color components arranged according to \fIFormat\fR\& \&. When \fIType\fR\& is one of \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE_2_3_3_REV\fR\& , \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_5_6_5_REV\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_4_4_4_4_REV\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT_1_5_5_5_REV\fR\& , \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_8_8_8_8_REV\fR\&, or \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT_2_10_10_10_REV\fR\&, each unsigned value is interpreted as containing all color components, specified by \fIFormat\fR\& , for a single pixel in a reversed order\&. Indices are always treated individually\&. Color components are treated as groups of one, two, three, or four values, again based on \fIFormat\fR\& \&. Both individual indices and groups of components are referred to as pixels\&. If \fIType\fR\& is \fI?GL_BITMAP\fR\&, the data must be unsigned bytes, and \fIFormat\fR\& must be either \fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\& or \fI?GL_STENCIL_INDEX\fR\&\&. Each unsigned byte is treated as eight 1-bit pixels, with bit ordering determined by \fI?GL_UNPACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\& (see \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& )\&.
.LP
width×height pixels are read from memory, starting at location \fIData\fR\& \&. By default, these pixels are taken from adjacent memory locations, except that after all \fIWidth\fR\& pixels are read, the read pointer is advanced to the next four-byte boundary\&. The four-byte row alignment is specified by \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_UNPACK_ALIGNMENT\fR\& , and it can be set to one, two, four, or eight bytes\&. Other pixel store parameters specify different read pointer advancements, both before the first pixel is read and after all \fIWidth\fR\& pixels are read\&. See the \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& reference page for details on these options\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a block of pixels is specified, \fIData\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
The width×height pixels that are read from memory are each operated on in the same way, based on the values of several parameters specified by \fBgl:pixelTransferf/2\fR\& and \fBgl:pixelMapfv/3\fR\& \&. The details of these operations, as well as the target buffer into which the pixels are drawn, are specific to the format of the pixels, as specified by \fIFormat\fR\& \&. \fIFormat\fR\& can assume one of 13 symbolic values:
.LP
\fI?GL_COLOR_INDEX\fR\&: Each pixel is a single value, a color index\&. It is converted to fixed-point format, with an unspecified number of bits to the right of the binary point, regardless of the memory data type\&. Floating-point values convert to true fixed-point values\&. Signed and unsigned integer data is converted with all fraction bits set to 0\&. Bitmap data convert to either 0 or 1\&.
.LP
Each fixed-point index is then shifted left by \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& bits and added to \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\& \&. If \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& is negative, the shift is to the right\&. In either case, zero bits fill otherwise unspecified bit locations in the result\&.
.LP
If the GL is in RGBA mode, the resulting index is converted to an RGBA pixel with the help of the \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_R\fR\&, \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_G\fR\&, \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_B\fR\& , and \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_A\fR\& tables\&. If the GL is in color index mode, and if \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is true, the index is replaced with the value that it references in lookup table \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_I_TO_I\fR\& \&. Whether the lookup replacement of the index is done or not, the integer part of the index is then ANDed with 2 b-1, where b is the number of bits in a color index buffer\&.
.LP
The GL then converts the resulting indices or RGBA colors to fragments by attaching the current raster position \fIz\fR\& coordinate and texture coordinates to each pixel, then assigning x and y window coordinates to the nth fragment such that x n=x r+n% width
.LP
y n=y r+|n/width|
.LP
where (x r y r) is the current raster position\&. These pixel fragments are then treated just like the fragments generated by rasterizing points, lines, or polygons\&. Texture mapping, fog, and all the fragment operations are applied before the fragments are written to the frame buffer\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_STENCIL_INDEX\fR\&: Each pixel is a single value, a stencil index\&. It is converted to fixed-point format, with an unspecified number of bits to the right of the binary point, regardless of the memory data type\&. Floating-point values convert to true fixed-point values\&. Signed and unsigned integer data is converted with all fraction bits set to 0\&. Bitmap data convert to either 0 or 1\&.
.LP
Each fixed-point index is then shifted left by \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& bits, and added to \fI?GL_INDEX_OFFSET\fR\&\&. If \fI?GL_INDEX_SHIFT\fR\& is negative, the shift is to the right\&. In either case, zero bits fill otherwise unspecified bit locations in the result\&. If \fI?GL_MAP_STENCIL\fR\& is true, the index is replaced with the value that it references in lookup table \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_S_TO_S\fR\&\&. Whether the lookup replacement of the index is done or not, the integer part of the index is then ANDed with 2 b-1, where b is the number of bits in the stencil buffer\&. The resulting stencil indices are then written to the stencil buffer such that the nth index is written to location
.LP
x n=x r+n% width
.LP
y n=y r+|n/width|
.LP
where (x r y r) is the current raster position\&. Only the pixel ownership test, the scissor test, and the stencil writemask affect these write operations\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_DEPTH_COMPONENT\fR\&: Each pixel is a single-depth component\&. Floating-point data is converted directly to an internal floating-point format with unspecified precision\&. Signed integer data is mapped linearly to the internal floating-point format such that the most positive representable integer value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Unsigned integer data is mapped similarly: the largest integer value maps to 1\&.0, and 0 maps to 0\&.0\&. The resulting floating-point depth value is then multiplied by \fI?GL_DEPTH_SCALE\fR\& and added to \fI?GL_DEPTH_BIAS\fR\&\&. The result is clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
The GL then converts the resulting depth components to fragments by attaching the current raster position color or color index and texture coordinates to each pixel, then assigning x and y window coordinates to the nth fragment such that
.LP
x n=x r+n% width
.LP
y n=y r+|n/width|
.LP
where (x r y r) is the current raster position\&. These pixel fragments are then treated just like the fragments generated by rasterizing points, lines, or polygons\&. Texture mapping, fog, and all the fragment operations are applied before the fragments are written to the frame buffer\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGRA\fR\&: Each pixel is a four-component group: For \fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&, the red component is first, followed by green, followed by blue, followed by alpha; for \fI?GL_BGRA\fR\& the order is blue, green, red and then alpha\&. Floating-point values are converted directly to an internal floating-point format with unspecified precision\&. Signed integer values are mapped linearly to the internal floating-point format such that the most positive representable integer value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. (Note that this mapping does not convert 0 precisely to 0\&.0\&.) Unsigned integer data is mapped similarly: The largest integer value maps to 1\&.0, and 0 maps to 0\&.0\&. The resulting floating-point color values are then multiplied by \fI?GL_c_SCALE\fR\& and added to \fI?GL_c_BIAS\fR\&, where \fIc\fR\& is RED, GREEN, BLUE, and ALPHA for the respective color components\&. The results are clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
If \fI?GL_MAP_COLOR\fR\& is true, each color component is scaled by the size of lookup table \fI?GL_PIXEL_MAP_c_TO_c\fR\&, then replaced by the value that it references in that table\&. \fIc\fR\& is R, G, B, or A respectively\&.
.LP
The GL then converts the resulting RGBA colors to fragments by attaching the current raster position \fIz\fR\& coordinate and texture coordinates to each pixel, then assigning x and y window coordinates to the nth fragment such that
.LP
x n=x r+n% width
.LP
y n=y r+|n/width|
.LP
where (x r y r) is the current raster position\&. These pixel fragments are then treated just like the fragments generated by rasterizing points, lines, or polygons\&. Texture mapping, fog, and all the fragment operations are applied before the fragments are written to the frame buffer\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RED\fR\&: Each pixel is a single red component\&. This component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the red component of an RGBA pixel is\&. It is then converted to an RGBA pixel with green and blue set to 0, and alpha set to 1\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_GREEN\fR\&: Each pixel is a single green component\&. This component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the green component of an RGBA pixel is\&. It is then converted to an RGBA pixel with red and blue set to 0, and alpha set to 1\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_BLUE\fR\&: Each pixel is a single blue component\&. This component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the blue component of an RGBA pixel is\&. It is then converted to an RGBA pixel with red and green set to 0, and alpha set to 1\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_ALPHA\fR\&: Each pixel is a single alpha component\&. This component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the alpha component of an RGBA pixel is\&. It is then converted to an RGBA pixel with red, green, and blue set to 0\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGR\fR\&: Each pixel is a three-component group: red first, followed by green, followed by blue; for \fI?GL_BGR\fR\&, the first component is blue, followed by green and then red\&. Each component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the red, green, and blue components of an RGBA pixel are\&. The color triple is converted to an RGBA pixel with alpha set to 1\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\&: Each pixel is a single luminance component\&. This component is converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the red component of an RGBA pixel is\&. It is then converted to an RGBA pixel with red, green, and blue set to the converted luminance value, and alpha set to 1\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\&: Each pixel is a two-component group: luminance first, followed by alpha\&. The two components are converted to the internal floating-point format in the same way the red component of an RGBA pixel is\&. They are then converted to an RGBA pixel with red, green, and blue set to the converted luminance value, and alpha set to the converted alpha value\&. After this conversion, the pixel is treated as if it had been read as an RGBA pixel\&.
.LP
The following table summarizes the meaning of the valid constants for the \fItype\fR\& parameter:\fIType\fR\&\fICorresponding Type\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE\fR\& unsigned 8-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_BYTE\fR\& signed 8-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_BITMAP\fR\& single bits in unsigned 8-bit integers 
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_SHORT\fR\& unsigned 16-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_SHORT\fR\& signed 16-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT\fR\& unsigned 32-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_INT\fR\& 32-bit integer 
.br
\fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\& single-precision floating-point 
.br
\fI?GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE_3_3_2\fR\& unsigned 8-bit integer 
