.LP
Set texture environment parameters
.LP
A texture environment specifies how texture values are interpreted when a fragment is textured\&. When \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_FILTER_CONTROL\fR\&, \fIPname\fR\& must be \fI?GL_TEXTURE_LOD_BIAS\fR\& \&. When \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV\fR\&, \fIPname\fR\& can be \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_MODE\fR\& , \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_COLOR\fR\&, \fI?GL_COMBINE_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_COMBINE_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_RGB_SCALE\fR\& , \fI?GL_ALPHA_SCALE\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC0_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC1_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC2_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC0_ALPHA\fR\& , \fI?GL_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\&, or \fI?GL_SRC2_ALPHA\fR\&\&.
.LP
If \fIPname\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_MODE\fR\&, then \fIParams\fR\& is (or points to) the symbolic name of a texture function\&. Six texture functions may be specified: \fI?GL_ADD\fR\& , \fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\&, \fI?GL_DECAL\fR\&, \fI?GL_BLEND\fR\&, \fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\&, or \fI?GL_COMBINE\fR\& \&.
.LP
The following table shows the correspondence of filtered texture values R t, G t, B t, A t, L t, I t to texture source components\&. C s and A s are used by the texture functions described below\&. Texture Base Internal Format C s A s
.br
\fI?GL_ALPHA\fR\& (0, 0, 0) A t
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\& ( L t, L t, L t ) 1 
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\& ( L t, L t, L t ) A t
.br
\fI?GL_INTENSITY\fR\& ( I t, I t, I t ) I t
.br
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\& ( R t, G t, B t ) 1 
.br
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& ( R t, G t, B t ) A t
.br

.LP
A texture function acts on the fragment to be textured using the texture image value that applies to the fragment (see \fBgl:texParameterf/3\fR\& ) and produces an RGBA color for that fragment\&. The following table shows how the RGBA color is produced for each of the first five texture functions that can be chosen\&. C is a triple of color values (RGB) and A is the associated alpha value\&. RGBA values extracted from a texture image are in the range [0,1]\&. The subscript p refers to the color computed from the previous texture stage (or the incoming fragment if processing texture stage 0), the subscript s to the texture source color, the subscript c to the texture environment color, and the subscript v indicates a value produced by the texture function\&. Texture Base Internal Format \fI?Value\fR\&\fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\& Function \fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\& Function \fI?GL_DECAL\fR\& Function \fI?GL_BLEND\fR\& Function \fI?GL_ADD\fR\& Function 
.br
\fI?GL_ALPHA\fR\& C v= C p C p undefined C p C p
.br
 A v= A s A p A s A v=A p A s A p A s
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\& C v= C s C p C s undefined C p (1-C s)+C c C s C p+C s
.br
 (or 1) A v= A p A p A p A p
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\& C v= C s C p C s undefined C p (1-C s)+C c C s C p+C s
.br
 (or 2) A v= A s A p A s A p A s A p A s 
.br
\fI?GL_INTENSITY\fR\& C v= C s C p C s undefined C p (1-C s)+C c C s C p+C s
.br
 A v= A s A p A s A p (1-A s)+A c A s A p+A s
.br
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\& C v= C s C p C s C s C p (1-C s)+C c C s C p+C s
.br
 (or 3) A v= A p A p A p A p A p
.br
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& C v= C s C p C s C p (1-A s)+C s A s C p (1-C s)+C c C s C p+C s
.br
 (or 4) A v= A s A p A s A p A p A s A p A s
.br

.LP
If \fIPname\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_MODE\fR\&, and \fIParams\fR\& is \fI?GL_COMBINE\fR\&, the form of the texture function depends on the values of \fI?GL_COMBINE_RGB\fR\& and \fI?GL_COMBINE_ALPHA\fR\& \&.
.LP
The following describes how the texture sources, as specified by \fI?GL_SRC0_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC1_RGB\fR\& , \fI?GL_SRC2_RGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC0_ALPHA\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\&, and \fI?GL_SRC2_ALPHA\fR\& , are combined to produce a final texture color\&. In the following tables, \fI?GL_SRC0_c\fR\& is represented by Arg0, \fI?GL_SRC1_c\fR\& is represented by Arg1, and \fI?GL_SRC2_c\fR\& is represented by Arg2\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_COMBINE_RGB\fR\& accepts any of \fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\&, \fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\&, \fI?GL_ADD\fR\& , \fI?GL_ADD_SIGNED\fR\&, \fI?GL_INTERPOLATE\fR\&, \fI?GL_SUBTRACT\fR\&, \fI?GL_DOT3_RGB\fR\&, or \fI?GL_DOT3_RGBA\fR\&\&.\fI?GL_COMBINE_RGB\fR\&\fITexture Function\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\& Arg0
.br
\fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\& Arg0×Arg1
.br
\fI?GL_ADD\fR\& Arg0+Arg1
.br
\fI?GL_ADD_SIGNED\fR\& Arg0+Arg1-0\&.5
.br
\fI?GL_INTERPOLATE\fR\& Arg0×Arg2+Arg1×(1- Arg2) 
.br
\fI?GL_SUBTRACT\fR\& Arg0-Arg1
.br
\fI?GL_DOT3_RGB\fR\& or \fI?GL_DOT3_RGBA\fR\& 4×((((Arg0 r)-0\&.5)×((Arg1 r)-0\&.5))+(((Arg0 g)-0\&.5)×((Arg1 g)-0\&.5))+(((Arg0 b)-0\&.5)×((Arg1 b)-0\&.5)))
.br

.LP
The scalar results for \fI?GL_DOT3_RGB\fR\& and \fI?GL_DOT3_RGBA\fR\& are placed into each of the 3 (RGB) or 4 (RGBA) components on output\&.
.LP
Likewise, \fI?GL_COMBINE_ALPHA\fR\& accepts any of \fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\&, \fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\&, \fI?GL_ADD\fR\&, \fI?GL_ADD_SIGNED\fR\&, \fI?GL_INTERPOLATE\fR\&, or \fI?GL_SUBTRACT\fR\&\&. The following table describes how alpha values are combined:\fI?GL_COMBINE_ALPHA\fR\&\fITexture Function\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_REPLACE\fR\& Arg0
.br
\fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\& Arg0×Arg1
.br
\fI?GL_ADD\fR\& Arg0+Arg1
.br
\fI?GL_ADD_SIGNED\fR\& Arg0+Arg1-0\&.5
.br
\fI?GL_INTERPOLATE\fR\& Arg0×Arg2+Arg1×(1- Arg2) 
.br
\fI?GL_SUBTRACT\fR\& Arg0-Arg1
.br

.LP
In the following tables, the value C s represents the color sampled from the currently bound texture, C c represents the constant texture-environment color, C f represents the primary color of the incoming fragment, and C p represents the color computed from the previous texture stage or C f if processing texture stage 0\&. Likewise, A s, A c, A f, and A p represent the respective alpha values\&.
.LP
The following table describes the values assigned to Arg0, Arg1, and Arg2 based upon the RGB sources and operands:\fI?GL_SRCn_RGB\fR\&\fI?GL_OPERANDn_RGB\fR\&\fIArgument Value\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_TEXTURE\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(C s) 
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& 1-(C s)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_TEXTUREn\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(C s)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& 1-(C s)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& (A s)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(C c)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& 1-(C c)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A c)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A c)
.br
\fI?GL_PRIMARY_COLOR\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(C f)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& 1-(C f)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A f)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A f)
.br
\fI?GL_PREVIOUS\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\& (C p)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& 1-(C p)
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A p)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A p)
.br

.LP
For \fI?GL_TEXTUREn\fR\& sources, C s and A s represent the color and alpha, respectively, produced from texture stage n\&.
.LP
The follow table describes the values assigned to Arg0, Arg1, and Arg2 based upon the alpha sources and operands:\fI?GL_SRCn_ALPHA\fR\&\fI?GL_OPERANDn_ALPHA\fR\&\fIArgument Value\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_TEXTURE\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A s) 
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_TEXTUREn\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A s)
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A c) 
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A c)
.br
\fI?GL_PRIMARY_COLOR\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A f)
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A f)
.br
\fI?GL_PREVIOUS\fR\&\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A p) 
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& 1-(A p)
.br

.LP
The RGB and alpha results of the texture function are multipled by the values of \fI?GL_RGB_SCALE\fR\& and \fI?GL_ALPHA_SCALE\fR\&, respectively, and clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
If \fIPname\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_COLOR\fR\&, \fIParams\fR\& is a pointer to an array that holds an RGBA color consisting of four values\&. Integer color components are interpreted linearly such that the most positive integer maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative integer maps to -1\&.0\&. The values are clamped to the range [0,1] when they are specified\&. C c takes these four values\&.
.LP
If \fIPname\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_LOD_BIAS\fR\&, the value specified is added to the texture level-of-detail parameter, that selects which mipmap, or mipmaps depending upon the selected \fI?GL_TEXTURE_MIN_FILTER\fR\&, will be sampled\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_MODE\fR\& defaults to \fI?GL_MODULATE\fR\& and \fI?GL_TEXTURE_ENV_COLOR\fR\& defaults to (0, 0, 0, 0)\&.
.LP
If \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_POINT_SPRITE\fR\& and \fIPname\fR\& is \fI?GL_COORD_REPLACE\fR\&, the boolean value specified is used to either enable or disable point sprite texture coordinate replacement\&. The default value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\&\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
