\fIgl:getTexLevelParameter\fR\& returns in \fIParams\fR\& texture parameter values for a specific level-of-detail value, specified as \fILevel\fR\& \&. \fITarget\fR\& defines the target texture, either \fI?GL_TEXTURE_1D\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_2D\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&, \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_1D\fR\& , \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_2D\fR\&, \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_POSITIVE_X\fR\& , \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_NEGATIVE_X\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_POSITIVE_Y\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_NEGATIVE_Y\fR\& , \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_POSITIVE_Z\fR\&, \fI?GL_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP_NEGATIVE_Z\fR\&, or \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_CUBE_MAP\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_MAX_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\&, and \fI?GL_MAX_3D_TEXTURE_SIZE\fR\& are not really descriptive enough\&. It has to report the largest square texture image that can be accommodated with mipmaps and borders, but a long skinny texture, or a texture without mipmaps and borders, may easily fit in texture memory\&. The proxy targets allow the user to more accurately query whether the GL can accommodate a texture of a given configuration\&. If the texture cannot be accommodated, the texture state variables, which may be queried with \fIgl:getTexLevelParameter\fR\& , are set to 0\&. If the texture can be accommodated, the texture state values will be set as they would be set for a non-proxy target\&.
.LP
\fIPname\fR\& specifies the texture parameter whose value or values will be returned\&.
.LP
The accepted parameter names are as follows:
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_WIDTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the width of the texture image\&. This value includes the border of the texture image\&. The initial value is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_HEIGHT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the height of the texture image\&. This value includes the border of the texture image\&. The initial value is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_DEPTH\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the depth of the texture image\&. This value includes the border of the texture image\&. The initial value is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_INTERNAL_FORMAT\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single value, the internal format of the texture image\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_RED_TYPE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_GREEN_TYPE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BLUE_TYPE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_ALPHA_TYPE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_DEPTH_TYPE\fR\&: The data type used to store the component\&. The types \fI?GL_NONE\fR\& , \fI?GL_SIGNED_NORMALIZED\fR\&, \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_NORMALIZED\fR\&, \fI?GL_FLOAT\fR\&, \fI?GL_INT\fR\& , and \fI?GL_UNSIGNED_INT\fR\& may be returned to indicate signed normalized fixed-point, unsigned normalized fixed-point, floating-point, integer unnormalized, and unsigned integer unnormalized components, respectively\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_RED_SIZE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_GREEN_SIZE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_BLUE_SIZE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_ALPHA_SIZE\fR\&,
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_DEPTH_SIZE\fR\&: The internal storage resolution of an individual component\&. The resolution chosen by the GL will be a close match for the resolution requested by the user with the component argument of \fBgl:texImage1D/8\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage2D/9\fR\& , \fBgl:texImage3D/10\fR\& , \fBgl:copyTexImage1D/7\fR\& , and \fBgl:copyTexImage2D/8\fR\& \&. The initial value is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_COMPRESSED\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single boolean value indicating if the texture image is stored in a compressed internal format\&. The initiali value is \fI?GL_FALSE\fR\& \&.
.LP
\fI?GL_TEXTURE_COMPRESSED_IMAGE_SIZE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& returns a single integer value, the number of unsigned bytes of the compressed texture image that would be returned from \fBgl:getCompressedTexImage/3\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
