evalMesh1(Mode, I1, I2) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
I1 = integer()
.br
I2 = integer()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Compute a one- or two-dimensional grid of points or lines
.LP
\fBgl:mapGrid1d/3\fR\& and \fIgl:evalMesh\fR\& are used in tandem to efficiently generate and evaluate a series of evenly-spaced map domain values\&. \fIgl:evalMesh\fR\& steps through the integer domain of a one- or two-dimensional grid, whose range is the domain of the evaluation maps specified by \fBgl:map1d/6\fR\& and \fBgl:map1d/6\fR\& \&. \fIMode\fR\& determines whether the resulting vertices are connected as points, lines, or filled polygons\&.
.LP
In the one-dimensional case, \fIgl:evalMesh1\fR\&, the mesh is generated as if the following code fragment were executed:
.LP
glBegin( \fIType\fR\& ); for ( i = \fII1\fR\& ; i <= \fII2\fR\& ; i += 1 ) glEvalCoord1( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1 ); glEnd(); where
.LP
&Delta; u=(u 2-u 1)/n
.LP
and n, u 1, and u 2 are the arguments to the most recent \fBgl:mapGrid1d/3\fR\& command\&. \fItype\fR\& is \fI?GL_POINTS\fR\& if \fIMode\fR\& is \fI?GL_POINT\fR\&, or \fI?GL_LINES\fR\& if \fIMode\fR\& is \fI?GL_LINE\fR\&\&.
.LP
The one absolute numeric requirement is that if i=n, then the value computed from i\&.&Delta; u+u 1 is exactly u 2\&.
.LP
In the two-dimensional case, \fIgl:evalMesh2\fR\&, let \&.cp &Delta; u=(u 2-u 1)/n
.LP
&Delta; v=(v 2-v 1)/m
.LP
where n, u 1, u 2, m, v 1, and v 2 are the arguments to the most recent \fBgl:mapGrid1d/3\fR\& command\&. Then, if \fIMode\fR\& is \fI?GL_FILL\fR\&, the \fIgl:evalMesh2\fR\& command is equivalent to:
.LP
for ( j = \fIJ1\fR\& ; j < \fIJ2\fR\& ; j += 1 ) { glBegin( GL_QUAD_STRIP ); for ( i = \fII1\fR\& ; i <= \fII2\fR\& ; i += 1 ) { glEvalCoord2( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1, j\&.&Delta; v+v 1 ); glEvalCoord2( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1,(j+1)\&.&Delta; v+v 1 ); } glEnd(); }
.LP
If \fIMode\fR\& is \fI?GL_LINE\fR\&, then a call to \fIgl:evalMesh2\fR\& is equivalent to:
.LP
for ( j = \fIJ1\fR\& ; j <= \fIJ2\fR\& ; j += 1 ) { glBegin( GL_LINE_STRIP ); for ( i = \fII1\fR\& ; i <= \fII2\fR\& ; i += 1 ) glEvalCoord2( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1, j\&.&Delta; v+v 1 ); glEnd(); } for ( i = \fII1\fR\& ; i <= \fII2\fR\& ; i += 1 ) { glBegin( GL_LINE_STRIP ); for ( j = \fIJ1\fR\& ; j <= \fIJ1\fR\& ; j += 1 ) glEvalCoord2( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1, j\&. &Delta; v+v 1 ); glEnd(); }
.LP
And finally, if \fIMode\fR\& is \fI?GL_POINT\fR\&, then a call to \fIgl:evalMesh2\fR\& is equivalent to:
.LP
glBegin( GL_POINTS ); for ( j = \fIJ1\fR\& ; j <= \fIJ2\fR\& ; j += 1 ) for ( i = \fII1\fR\& ; i <= \fII2\fR\& ; i += 1 ) glEvalCoord2( i\&.&Delta; u+u 1, j\&.&Delta; v+v 1 ); glEnd();
.LP
In all three cases, the only absolute numeric requirements are that if i=n, then the value computed from i\&.&Delta; u+u 1 is exactly u 2, and if j=m, then the value computed from j\&.&Delta; v+v 1 is exactly v 2\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
