.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Pname = enum()
.br
Param = float()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify fog parameters
.LP
Fog is initially disabled\&. While enabled, fog affects rasterized geometry, bitmaps, and pixel blocks, but not buffer clear operations\&. To enable and disable fog, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_FOG\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fIgl:fog\fR\& assigns the value or values in \fIParams\fR\& to the fog parameter specified by \fIPname\fR\& \&. The following values are accepted for \fIPname\fR\& :
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_MODE\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies the equation to be used to compute the fog blend factor, f\&. Three symbolic constants are accepted: \fI?GL_LINEAR\fR\&, \fI?GL_EXP\fR\&, and \fI?GL_EXP2\fR\&\&. The equations corresponding to these symbolic constants are defined below\&. The initial fog mode is \fI?GL_EXP\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_DENSITY\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies density, the fog density used in both exponential fog equations\&. Only nonnegative densities are accepted\&. The initial fog density is 1\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_START\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies start, the near distance used in the linear fog equation\&. The initial near distance is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_END\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies end, the far distance used in the linear fog equation\&. The initial far distance is 1\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_INDEX\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& is a single integer or floating-point value that specifies i f, the fog color index\&. The initial fog index is 0\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_COLOR\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains four integer or floating-point values that specify C f, the fog color\&. Integer values are mapped linearly such that the most positive representable value maps to 1\&.0, and the most negative representable value maps to -1\&.0\&. Floating-point values are mapped directly\&. After conversion, all color components are clamped to the range [0 1]\&. The initial fog color is (0, 0, 0, 0)\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_FOG_COORD_SRC\fR\&: \fIParams\fR\& contains either of the following symbolic constants: \fI?GL_FOG_COORD\fR\& or \fI?GL_FRAGMENT_DEPTH\fR\&\&. \fI?GL_FOG_COORD\fR\& specifies that the current fog coordinate should be used as distance value in the fog color computation\&. \fI?GL_FRAGMENT_DEPTH\fR\& specifies that the current fragment depth should be used as distance value in the fog computation\&.
.LP
Fog blends a fog color with each rasterized pixel fragment\&'s post-texturing color using a blending factor f\&. Factor f is computed in one of three ways, depending on the fog mode\&. Let c be either the distance in eye coordinate from the origin (in the case that the \fI?GL_FOG_COORD_SRC\fR\& is \fI?GL_FRAGMENT_DEPTH\fR\&) or the current fog coordinate (in the case that \fI?GL_FOG_COORD_SRC\fR\& is \fI?GL_FOG_COORD\fR\&)\&. The equation for \fI?GL_LINEAR\fR\& fog is f=(end-c)/(end-start)
.LP
The equation for \fI?GL_EXP\fR\& fog is f=e(-(density\&. c))
.LP
The equation for \fI?GL_EXP2\fR\& fog is f=e(-(density\&. c)) 2
.LP
Regardless of the fog mode, f is clamped to the range [0 1] after it is computed\&. Then, if the GL is in RGBA color mode, the fragment\&'s red, green, and blue colors, represented by C r, are replaced by
.LP
(C r)"=f×C r+(1-f)×C f
.LP
Fog does not affect a fragment\&'s alpha component\&.
.LP
In color index mode, the fragment\&'s color index i r is replaced by
.LP
(i r)"=i r+(1-f)×i f
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
