.B
blendEquation(Mode) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify the equation used for both the RGB blend equation and the Alpha blend equation
.LP
The blend equations determine how a new pixel (the \&'\&'source\&'\&' color) is combined with a pixel already in the framebuffer (the \&'\&'destination\&'\&' color)\&. This function sets both the RGB blend equation and the alpha blend equation to a single equation\&. \fIgl:blendEquationi\fR\& specifies the blend equation for a single draw buffer whereas \fIgl:blendEquation\fR\& sets the blend equation for all draw buffers\&.
.LP
These equations use the source and destination blend factors specified by either \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& or \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& \&. See \fBgl:blendFunc/2\fR\& or \fBgl:blendFuncSeparate/4\fR\& for a description of the various blend factors\&.
.LP
In the equations that follow, source and destination color components are referred to as (R s G s B s A s) and (R d G d B d A d), respectively\&. The result color is referred to as (R r G r B r A r)\&. The source and destination blend factors are denoted (s R s G s B s A) and (d R d G d B d A), respectively\&. For these equations all color components are understood to have values in the range [0 1]\&.\fIMode\fR\&\fIRGB Components\fR\&\fIAlpha Component\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_FUNC_ADD\fR\& Rr=R s s R+R d d R Gr=G s s G+G d d G Br=B s s B+B d d B Ar=A s s A+A d d A
.br
\fI?GL_FUNC_SUBTRACT\fR\& Rr=R s s R-R d d R Gr=G s s G-G d d G Br=B s s B-B d d B Ar=A s s A-A d d A
.br
\fI?GL_FUNC_REVERSE_SUBTRACT\fR\& Rr=R d d R-R s s R Gr=G d d G-G s s G Br=B d d B-B s s B Ar=A d d A-A s s A
.br
\fI?GL_MIN\fR\& Rr=min(R s R d) Gr=min(G s G d) Br=min(B s B d) Ar=min (A s A d)
.br
\fI?GL_MAX\fR\& Rr=max(R s R d) Gr=max(G s G d) Br=max(B s B d) Ar=max(A s A d)
.br

.LP
The results of these equations are clamped to the range [0 1]\&.
.LP
The \fI?GL_MIN\fR\& and \fI?GL_MAX\fR\& equations are useful for applications that analyze image data (image thresholding against a constant color, for example)\&. The \fI?GL_FUNC_ADD\fR\& equation is useful for antialiasing and transparency, among other things\&.
.LP
Initially, both the RGB blend equation and the alpha blend equation are set to \fI?GL_FUNC_ADD\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
drawRangeElements(Mode, Start, End, Count, Type, Indices) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

