.RS
.LP
Specify a three-dimensional texture image
.LP
Texturing maps a portion of a specified texture image onto each graphical primitive for which texturing is enabled\&. To enable and disable three-dimensional texturing, call \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&\&.
.LP
To define texture images, call \fIgl:texImage3D\fR\&\&. The arguments describe the parameters of the texture image, such as height, width, depth, width of the border, level-of-detail number (see \fBgl:texParameterf/3\fR\& ), and number of color components provided\&. The last three arguments describe how the image is represented in memory\&.
.LP
If \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&, no data is read from \fIData\fR\& , but all of the texture image state is recalculated, checked for consistency, and checked against the implementation\&'s capabilities\&. If the implementation cannot handle a texture of the requested texture size, it sets all of the image state to 0, but does not generate an error (see \fBgl:getError/0\fR\& )\&. To query for an entire mipmap array, use an image array level greater than or equal to 1\&.
.LP
If \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_TEXTURE_3D\fR\&, data is read from \fIData\fR\& as a sequence of signed or unsigned bytes, shorts, or longs, or single-precision floating-point values, depending on \fIType\fR\& \&. These values are grouped into sets of one, two, three, or four values, depending on \fIFormat\fR\& , to form elements\&. Each data byte is treated as eight 1-bit elements, with bit ordering determined by \fI?GL_UNPACK_LSB_FIRST\fR\& (see \fBgl:pixelStoref/2\fR\& )\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a texture image is specified, \fIData\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
The first element corresponds to the lower left corner of the texture image\&. Subsequent elements progress left-to-right through the remaining texels in the lowest row of the texture image, and then in successively higher rows of the texture image\&. The final element corresponds to the upper right corner of the texture image\&.
.LP
\fIFormat\fR\& determines the composition of each element in \fIData\fR\& \&. It can assume one of these symbolic values:
.LP
\fI?GL_RED\fR\&: Each element is a single red component\&. The GL converts it to floating point and assembles it into an RGBA element by attaching 0 for green and blue, and 1 for alpha\&. Each component is then multiplied by the signed scale factor \fI?GL_c_SCALE\fR\&, added to the signed bias \fI?GL_c_BIAS\fR\&, and clamped to the range [0,1]\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RG\fR\&: Each element is a red and green pair\&. The GL converts each to floating point and assembles it into an RGBA element by attaching 0 for blue, and 1 for alpha\&. Each component is then multiplied by the signed scale factor \fI?GL_c_SCALE\fR\&, added to the signed bias \fI?GL_c_BIAS\fR\&, and clamped to the range [0,1]\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGR\fR\&: Each element is an RGB triple\&. The GL converts it to floating point and assembles it into an RGBA element by attaching 1 for alpha\&. Each component is then multiplied by the signed scale factor \fI?GL_c_SCALE\fR\&, added to the signed bias \fI?GL_c_BIAS\fR\&, and clamped to the range [0,1]\&.
.LP
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&
.LP
\fI?GL_BGRA\fR\&: Each element contains all four components\&. Each component is multiplied by the signed scale factor \fI?GL_c_SCALE\fR\&, added to the signed bias \fI?GL_c_BIAS\fR\&, and clamped to the range [0,1]\&.
.LP
If an application wants to store the texture at a certain resolution or in a certain format, it can request the resolution and format with \fIInternalFormat\fR\& \&. The GL will choose an internal representation that closely approximates that requested by \fIInternalFormat\fR\& , but it may not match exactly\&. (The representations specified by \fI?GL_RED\fR\&, \fI?GL_RG\fR\& , \fI?GL_RGB\fR\&, and \fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& must match exactly\&.)
.LP
\fIInternalFormat\fR\& may be one of the base internal formats shown in Table 1, below
.LP
\fIInternalFormat\fR\& may also be one of the sized internal formats shown in Table 2, below
.LP
Finally, \fIInternalFormat\fR\& may also be one of the generic or compressed compressed texture formats shown in Table 3 below
.LP
If the \fIInternalFormat\fR\& parameter is one of the generic compressed formats, \fI?GL_COMPRESSED_RED\fR\& , \fI?GL_COMPRESSED_RG\fR\&, \fI?GL_COMPRESSED_RGB\fR\&, or \fI?GL_COMPRESSED_RGBA\fR\&, the GL will replace the internal format with the symbolic constant for a specific internal format and compress the texture before storage\&. If no corresponding internal format is available, or the GL can not compress that image for any reason, the internal format is instead replaced with a corresponding base internal format\&.
.LP
If the \fIInternalFormat\fR\& parameter is \fI?GL_SRGB\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRGB8\fR\&, \fI?GL_SRGB_ALPHA\fR\& , or \fI?GL_SRGB8_ALPHA8\fR\&, the texture is treated as if the red, green, blue, or luminance components are encoded in the sRGB color space\&. Any alpha component is left unchanged\&. The conversion from the sRGB encoded component c s to a linear component c l is:
.LP
c l={ c s/12\&.92if c s&le; 0\&.04045( c s+0\&.055/1\&.055) 2\&.4if c s> 0\&.04045
.LP
Assume c s is the sRGB component in the range [0,1]\&.
.LP
Use the \fI?GL_PROXY_TEXTURE_3D\fR\& target to try out a resolution and format\&. The implementation will update and recompute its best match for the requested storage resolution and format\&. To then query this state, call \fBgl:getTexLevelParameterfv/3\fR\& \&. If the texture cannot be accommodated, texture state is set to 0\&.
.LP
A one-component texture image uses only the red component of the RGBA color extracted from \fIData\fR\& \&. A two-component image uses the R and A values\&. A three-component image uses the R, G, and B values\&. A four-component image uses all of the RGBA components\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
