.RS
.LP
Copy a three-dimensional texture subimage
.LP
\fIgl:copyTexSubImage3D\fR\& replaces a rectangular portion of a three-dimensional texture image with pixels from the current \fI?GL_READ_BUFFER\fR\& (rather than from main memory, as is the case for \fBgl:texSubImage1D/7\fR\& )\&.
.LP
The screen-aligned pixel rectangle with lower left corner at ( \fIX\fR\& , \fIY\fR\& ) and with width \fIWidth\fR\& and height \fIHeight\fR\& replaces the portion of the texture array with x indices \fIXoffset\fR\& through xoffset+width-1, inclusive, and y indices \fIYoffset\fR\& through yoffset+height-1, inclusive, at z index \fIZoffset\fR\& and at the mipmap level specified by \fILevel\fR\& \&.
.LP
The pixels in the rectangle are processed exactly as if \fBgl:readPixels/7\fR\& had been called, but the process stops just before final conversion\&. At this point, all pixel component values are clamped to the range [0 1] and then converted to the texture\&'s internal format for storage in the texel array\&.
.LP
The destination rectangle in the texture array may not include any texels outside the texture array as it was originally specified\&. It is not an error to specify a subtexture with zero width or height, but such a specification has no effect\&.
.LP
If any of the pixels within the specified rectangle of the current \fI?GL_READ_BUFFER\fR\& are outside the read window associated with the current rendering context, then the values obtained for those pixels are undefined\&.
.LP
No change is made to the \fIinternalformat\fR\&, \fIwidth\fR\&, \fIheight\fR\&, \fIdepth\fR\&, or \fIborder\fR\& parameters of the specified texture array or to texel values outside the specified subregion\&.
