.LP
.B
colorTable(Target, Internalformat, Width, Format, Type, Table) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Target = enum()
.br
Internalformat = enum()
.br
Width = integer()
.br
Format = enum()
.br
Type = enum()
.br
Table = offset() | mem()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Define a color lookup table
.LP
\fIgl:colorTable\fR\& may be used in two ways: to test the actual size and color resolution of a lookup table given a particular set of parameters, or to load the contents of a color lookup table\&. Use the targets \fI?GL_PROXY_*\fR\& for the first case and the other targets for the second case\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a color table is specified, \fIData\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
If \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE\fR\&, \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_COLOR_TABLE\fR\&, or \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_COLOR_TABLE\fR\& , \fIgl:colorTable\fR\& builds a color lookup table from an array of pixels\&. The pixel array specified by \fIWidth\fR\& , \fIFormat\fR\& , \fIType\fR\& , and \fIData\fR\& is extracted from memory and processed just as if \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& were called, but processing stops after the final expansion to RGBA is completed\&.
.LP
The four scale parameters and the four bias parameters that are defined for the table are then used to scale and bias the R, G, B, and A components of each pixel\&. (Use \fIgl:colorTableParameter\fR\& to set these scale and bias parameters\&.)
.LP
Next, the R, G, B, and A values are clamped to the range [0 1]\&. Each pixel is then converted to the internal format specified by \fIInternalformat\fR\& \&. This conversion simply maps the component values of the pixel (R, G, B, and A) to the values included in the internal format (red, green, blue, alpha, luminance, and intensity)\&. The mapping is as follows:\fIInternal Format\fR\&\fIRed\fR\&\fIGreen\fR\&\fIBlue\fR\&\fIAlpha\fR\&\fILuminance\fR\&\fIIntensity\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_ALPHA\fR\& A 
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\& R 
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\& A R 
.br
\fI?GL_INTENSITY\fR\& R 
.br
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\& R G B 
.br
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& R G B A 
.br

.LP
Finally, the red, green, blue, alpha, luminance, and/or intensity components of the resulting pixels are stored in the color table\&. They form a one-dimensional table with indices in the range [0 width-1]\&.
.LP
If \fITarget\fR\& is \fI?GL_PROXY_*\fR\&, \fIgl:colorTable\fR\& recomputes and stores the values of the proxy color table\&'s state variables \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_FORMAT\fR\&, \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_WIDTH\fR\& , \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_RED_SIZE\fR\&, \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_GREEN_SIZE\fR\&, \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_BLUE_SIZE\fR\& , \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_ALPHA_SIZE\fR\&, \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_LUMINANCE_SIZE\fR\&, and \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE_INTENSITY_SIZE\fR\& \&. There is no effect on the image or state of any actual color table\&. If the specified color table is too large to be supported, then all the proxy state variables listed above are set to zero\&. Otherwise, the color table could be supported by \fIgl:colorTable\fR\& using the corresponding non-proxy target, and the proxy state variables are set as if that target were being defined\&.
.LP
The proxy state variables can be retrieved by calling \fBgl:getColorTableParameterfv/2\fR\& with a target of \fI?GL_PROXY_*\fR\&\&. This allows the application to decide if a particular \fIgl:colorTable\fR\& command would succeed, and to determine what the resulting color table attributes would be\&.
.LP
If a color table is enabled, and its width is non-zero, then its contents are used to replace a subset of the components of each RGBA pixel group, based on the internal format of the table\&.
.LP
Each pixel group has color components (R, G, B, A) that are in the range [0\&.0 1\&.0]\&. The color components are rescaled to the size of the color lookup table to form an index\&. Then a subset of the components based on the internal format of the table are replaced by the table entry selected by that index\&. If the color components and contents of the table are represented as follows:\fIRepresentation\fR\&\fIMeaning\fR\&
.br
 r Table index computed from R
.br
g Table index computed from G
.br
b Table index computed from B
.br
a Table index computed from A
.br
L[i] Luminance value at table index i
.br
I[i] Intensity value at table index i
.br
 R[i] Red value at table index i
.br
G[i] Green value at table index i
.br
B[i] Blue value at table index i
.br
 A[i] Alpha value at table index i
.br

.LP
then the result of color table lookup is as follows:\fIResulting Texture Components\fR\&
.br
\fITable Internal Format\fR\&\fIR\fR\&\fIG\fR\&\fIB\fR\&\fIA\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_ALPHA\fR\&RGBA[a]
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\&L[r]L[g]L[b]At
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\& L[r]L[g]L[b]A[a]
.br
\fI?GL_INTENSITY\fR\& I[r]I[g]I[b]I[a]
.br
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\&R[r] G[g]B[b]A
.br
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\&R[r] G[g]B[b]A[a]
.br

.LP
When \fI?GL_COLOR_TABLE\fR\& is enabled, the colors resulting from the pixel map operation (if it is enabled) are mapped by the color lookup table before being passed to the convolution operation\&. The colors resulting from the convolution operation are modified by the post convolution color lookup table when \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_COLOR_TABLE\fR\& is enabled\&. These modified colors are then sent to the color matrix operation\&. Finally, if \fI?GL_POST_COLOR_MATRIX_COLOR_TABLE\fR\& is enabled, the colors resulting from the color matrix operation are mapped by the post color matrix color lookup table before being used by the histogram operation\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
colorTableParameterfv(Target, Pname, Params) -> ok
