separableFilter2D(Target, Internalformat, Width, Height, Format, Type, Row, Column) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Target = enum()
.br
Internalformat = enum()
.br
Width = integer()
.br
Height = integer()
.br
Format = enum()
.br
Type = enum()
.br
Row = offset() | mem()
.br
Column = offset() | mem()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Define a separable two-dimensional convolution filter
.LP
\fIgl:separableFilter2D\fR\& builds a two-dimensional separable convolution filter kernel from two arrays of pixels\&.
.LP
The pixel arrays specified by ( \fIWidth\fR\& , \fIFormat\fR\& , \fIType\fR\& , \fIRow\fR\& ) and ( \fIHeight\fR\& , \fIFormat\fR\& , \fIType\fR\& , \fIColumn\fR\& ) are processed just as if they had been passed to \fBgl:drawPixels/5\fR\& , but processing stops after the final expansion to RGBA is completed\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_PIXEL_UNPACK_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a convolution filter is specified, \fIRow\fR\& and \fIColumn\fR\& are treated as byte offsets into the buffer object\&'s data store\&.
.LP
Next, the R, G, B, and A components of all pixels in both arrays are scaled by the four separable 2D \fI?GL_CONVOLUTION_FILTER_SCALE\fR\& parameters and biased by the four separable 2D \fI?GL_CONVOLUTION_FILTER_BIAS\fR\& parameters\&. (The scale and bias parameters are set by \fBgl:convolutionParameterf/3\fR\& using the \fI?GL_SEPARABLE_2D\fR\& target and the names \fI?GL_CONVOLUTION_FILTER_SCALE\fR\& and \fI?GL_CONVOLUTION_FILTER_BIAS\fR\&\&. The parameters themselves are vectors of four values that are applied to red, green, blue, and alpha, in that order\&.) The R, G, B, and A values are not clamped to [0,1] at any time during this process\&.
.LP
Each pixel is then converted to the internal format specified by \fIInternalformat\fR\& \&. This conversion simply maps the component values of the pixel (R, G, B, and A) to the values included in the internal format (red, green, blue, alpha, luminance, and intensity)\&. The mapping is as follows:\fIInternal Format\fR\&\fIRed\fR\&\fIGreen\fR\&\fIBlue\fR\&\fIAlpha\fR\&\fILuminance\fR\&\fIIntensity\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE\fR\& R 
.br
\fI?GL_LUMINANCE_ALPHA\fR\& A R 
.br
\fI?GL_INTENSITY\fR\& R 
.br
\fI?GL_RGB\fR\& R G B 
.br
\fI?GL_RGBA\fR\& R G B A 
.br

.LP
The red, green, blue, alpha, luminance, and/or intensity components of the resulting pixels are stored in floating-point rather than integer format\&. They form two one-dimensional filter kernel images\&. The row image is indexed by coordinate \fIi\fR\& starting at zero and increasing from left to right\&. Each location in the row image is derived from element \fIi\fR\& of \fIRow\fR\& \&. The column image is indexed by coordinate \fIj\fR\& starting at zero and increasing from bottom to top\&. Each location in the column image is derived from element \fIj\fR\& of \fIColumn\fR\& \&.
.LP
Note that after a convolution is performed, the resulting color components are also scaled by their corresponding \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_c_SCALE\fR\& parameters and biased by their corresponding \fI?GL_POST_CONVOLUTION_c_BIAS\fR\& parameters (where \fIc\fR\& takes on the values \fIRED\fR\&, \fIGREEN\fR\&, \fIBLUE\fR\&, and \fIALPHA\fR\&)\&. These parameters are set by \fBgl:pixelTransferf/2\fR\& \&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
