.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
M = matrix()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Replace the current matrix with the specified row-major ordered matrix
.LP
\fIgl:loadTransposeMatrix\fR\& replaces the current matrix with the one whose elements are specified by \fIM\fR\& \&. The current matrix is the projection matrix, modelview matrix, or texture matrix, depending on the current matrix mode (see \fBgl:matrixMode/1\fR\& )\&.
.LP
The current matrix, M, defines a transformation of coordinates\&. For instance, assume M refers to the modelview matrix\&. If v=(v[0] v[1] v[2] v[3]) is the set of object coordinates of a vertex, and \fIM\fR\& points to an array of 16 single- or double-precision floating-point values m={m[0] m[1] \&.\&.\&. m[15]}, then the modelview transformation M(v) does the following:
.LP
M(v)=(m[0] m[1] m[2] m[3] m[4] m[5] m[6] m[7] m[8] m[9] m[10] m[11] m[12] m[13] m[14] m[15])×(v[0] v[1] v[2] v[3])
.LP
Projection and texture transformations are similarly defined\&.
.LP
Calling \fIgl:loadTransposeMatrix\fR\& with matrix M is identical in operation to \fBgl:loadMatrixd/1\fR\& with M T, where T represents the transpose\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
