.B
blendFuncSeparate(SfactorRGB, DfactorRGB, SfactorAlpha, DfactorAlpha) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
SfactorRGB = enum()
.br
DfactorRGB = enum()
.br
SfactorAlpha = enum()
.br
DfactorAlpha = enum()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Specify pixel arithmetic for RGB and alpha components separately
.LP
Pixels can be drawn using a function that blends the incoming (source) RGBA values with the RGBA values that are already in the frame buffer (the destination values)\&. Blending is initially disabled\&. Use \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enable/1\fR\& with argument \fI?GL_BLEND\fR\& to enable and disable blending\&.
.LP
\fIgl:blendFuncSeparate\fR\& defines the operation of blending for all draw buffers when it is enabled\&. \fIgl:blendFuncSeparatei\fR\& defines the operation of blending for a single draw buffer specified by \fIBuf\fR\& when enabled for that draw buffer\&. \fISrcRGB\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the source RGB-color components\&. \fIDstRGB\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the destination RGB-color components\&. Likewise, \fISrcAlpha\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the source alpha color component, and \fIDstAlpha\fR\& specifies which method is used to scale the destination alpha component\&. The possible methods are described in the following table\&. Each method defines four scale factors, one each for red, green, blue, and alpha\&.
.LP
In the table and in subsequent equations, first source, second source and destination color components are referred to as (R s0 G s0 B s0 A s0), (R s1 G s1 B s1 A s1), and (R d G d B d A d), respectively\&. The color specified by \fBgl:blendColor/4\fR\& is referred to as (R c G c B c A c)\&. They are understood to have integer values between 0 and (k R k G k B k A), where
.LP
k c=2(m c)-1
.LP
and (m R m G m B m A) is the number of red, green, blue, and alpha bitplanes\&.
.LP
Source and destination scale factors are referred to as (s R s G s B s A) and (d R d G d B d A)\&. All scale factors have range [0 1]\&.\fIParameter\fR\&\fIRGB Factor\fR\&\fIAlpha Factor\fR\&
.br
\fI?GL_ZERO\fR\&(0 0 0) 0
.br
\fI?GL_ONE\fR\& (1 1 1) 1
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(R s0 k/R G s0 k/G B s0 k/B) A s0 k/A 
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1 1)-(R s0 k/R G s0 k/G B s0 k/B) 1-A s0 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_DST_COLOR\fR\&(R d k/R G d k/G B d k/B) A d k/A
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_COLOR\fR\& (1 1 1)-(R d k/R G d k/G B d k/B) 1-A d k/A
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A) A s0 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(1 1 1)-(A s0 k/A A s0 k/A A s0 k/A ) 1-A s0 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_DST_ALPHA\fR\&(A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A) A d k/A
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_DST_ALPHA\fR\& (1 1 1)-(A d k/A A d k/A A d k/A) 1-A d k/A
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\&(R c G c B c) A c
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_COLOR\fR\&(1 1 1)-(R c G c B c) 1-A c
.br
\fI?GL_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\&(A c A c A c) A c
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_CONSTANT_ALPHA\fR\& (1 1 1)-(A c A c A c) 1-A c
.br
\fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA_SATURATE\fR\&(i i i) 1
.br
\fI?GL_SRC1_COLOR\fR\&(R s1 k/R G s1 k/G B s1 k/B) A s1 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_COLOR\fR\& (1 1 1 1)-(R s1 k/R G s1 k/G B s1 k/B) 1-A s1 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_SRC1_ALPHA\fR\&(A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A) A s1 k/A
.br
\fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&(1 1 1)-(A s1 k/A A s1 k/A A s1 k/A ) 1-A s1 k/A
.br

.LP
In the table,
.LP
i=min(A s 1-(A d))
.LP
To determine the blended RGBA values of a pixel, the system uses the following equations:
.LP
R d=min(k R R s s R+R d d R) G d=min(k G G s s G+G d d G) B d=min(k B B s s B+B d d B) A d=min(k A A s s A+A d d A)
.LP
Despite the apparent precision of the above equations, blending arithmetic is not exactly specified, because blending operates with imprecise integer color values\&. However, a blend factor that should be equal to 1 is guaranteed not to modify its multiplicand, and a blend factor equal to 0 reduces its multiplicand to 0\&. For example, when \fISrcRGB\fR\& is \fI?GL_SRC_ALPHA\fR\& , \fIDstRGB\fR\& is \fI?GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA\fR\&, and A s is equal to k A, the equations reduce to simple replacement:
.LP
R d=R s G d=G s B d=B s A d=A s
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
.LP
.B
multiDrawArrays(Mode, First, Count) -> ok
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Mode = enum()
.br
First = [integer()]
.br
Count = [integer()]
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Render multiple sets of primitives from array data
.LP
\fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\& specifies multiple sets of geometric primitives with very few subroutine calls\&. Instead of calling a GL procedure to pass each individual vertex, normal, texture coordinate, edge flag, or color, you can prespecify separate arrays of vertices, normals, and colors and use them to construct a sequence of primitives with a single call to \fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\&\&.
.LP
\fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\& behaves identically to \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& except that \fIPrimcount\fR\& separate ranges of elements are specified instead\&.
.LP
When \fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\& is called, it uses \fICount\fR\& sequential elements from each enabled array to construct a sequence of geometric primitives, beginning with element \fIFirst\fR\& \&. \fIMode\fR\& specifies what kind of primitives are constructed, and how the array elements construct those primitives\&.
.LP
Vertex attributes that are modified by \fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\& have an unspecified value after \fIgl:multiDrawArrays\fR\& returns\&. Attributes that aren\&'t modified remain well defined\&.
.LP
See external documentation\&.
.RE
