.LP
\fIgl:fogCoordPointer\fR\& specifies the location and data format of an array of fog coordinates to use when rendering\&. \fIType\fR\& specifies the data type of each fog coordinate, and \fIStride\fR\& specifies the byte stride from one fog coordinate to the next, allowing vertices and attributes to be packed into a single array or stored in separate arrays\&.
.LP
If a non-zero named buffer object is bound to the \fI?GL_ARRAY_BUFFER\fR\& target (see \fBgl:bindBuffer/2\fR\& ) while a fog coordinate array is specified, \fIPointer\fR\& is treated as a byte offset into the buffer object\&'s data store\&. Also, the buffer object binding (\fI?GL_ARRAY_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\& ) is saved as fog coordinate vertex array client-side state (\fI?GL_FOG_COORD_ARRAY_BUFFER_BINDING\fR\& )\&.
.LP
When a fog coordinate array is specified, \fIType\fR\& , \fIStride\fR\& , and \fIPointer\fR\& are saved as client-side state, in addition to the current vertex array buffer object binding\&.
.LP
To enable and disable the fog coordinate array, call \fBgl:enableClientState/1\fR\& and \fBgl:enableClientState/1\fR\& with the argument \fI?GL_FOG_COORD_ARRAY\fR\&\&. If enabled, the fog coordinate array is used when \fBgl:drawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:multiDrawArrays/3\fR\& , \fBgl:drawElements/4\fR\& , see \fIglMultiDrawElements\fR\& , \fBgl:drawRangeElements/6\fR\& , or \fBgl:arrayElement/1\fR\& is called\&.
